<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 15:00 GMT, August 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- A formal recommendation to move South African
parliament to Pretoria is currently considered by a special
working committee of the ruling African National Congress (ANC).
Under the recommendation, parliament will be moved to Pretoria
from Cape Town and the Parliamentary Complex will be sold for some
58 million U.S. Dollars, a local newspaper "City Press" reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Germans tend to be too suspicious of the commercial
development of the Internet computer network, thus falling far
behind in its commercial use, the German subsidiary of the
U.S. computer giant Hewlett-Packard (HP) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
While German companies were generally interested in the
potential of the Internet as a business tool, they've been
relatively slow to adopt it, said Joerg Menno Harms, head of the
HP's German subsidiary, in an interview with the German news
agency DPA. (Germany-Internet)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia will voice its stand in efforts to
curb currency manipulations at the Commonwealth Finance Ministers
meeting in Mauritius next month, its Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We are firm in our stand to ensure there are joint efforts to
fight rogue speculators who meddle with international currencies,"
Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said in Pulau Pinang,
according to official media reports here. (Malaysia-Currency
Manipulation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Eight people were killed and 22 others injured in
two railroad explosions, informed Algerian sources said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The explosions occurred Saturday while a train was traveling
from Algiers to the town of Khamis Maliana, 150 kilometers south
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The first bomb laid on the railroad went off when the train was
running and damaged the front passenger carriage, while the second
one laid on a road near the railroad exploded a few moments after
the first blast. (Algeria-Bomb)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea will channel 10 million U.S. dollars worth
of food, medicine and farming implements to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), the Ministry of National
Unification announced over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the aid package, to be delivered through the
U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), will mainly benefit children in
DPRK. (SKorea-DPRK-Aid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq exported more than 13.5 million barrels of
crude over the past eight days under its renewed oil-for-food deal
with the United Nations, Iraqi newspaper Al-Qadissiya said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This is roughly in keeping with the country's projected oil
export capacity of 1.8 million barrels a day. Iraq has to speed up
crude export to fit into a cut-off period ending December
6. (Iraq-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu arrived here
Sunday on an four-day visit for talks with his Japanese
counterpart, Ryutaro Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is the second Israeli prime minister to visit Japan
following late Yitzhak Rabin who visited Tokyo in December
1994. (Japan-Israel-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- Zambian police Sunday denied that the police fired at
ex-president Kenneth David Kaunda who tried to address an
opposition rally Saturday in central town of Kabwe, the Zambia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Standwell Lungu also denied that the police
fired bullets at Kaunda's supporters to disrupt the rally.
</P>
<P>
The police only used "tear gas cannisters" to disperse the
people, the spokesman said. (Zambia-Kaunda, Opposition Rally)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair is preparing to
meet Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams within the next few weeks in a
historic move which will set the seal on Sinn Fein's involvement
in full-scale negotiations on the future of Northern Ireland, The
Sunday Telegraph reported. (UK-Northern Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait Sunday strongly condemned Israel for its
latest bombardment against Lebanese targets and urged the
international community to take immediate measures to stop the
military operations on civilians and revive the deadlocked Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Minister of State for Cabinet Affairs Abdul Aziz
Al-Dakhil made the condemnation after a weekly cabinet meeting
here.
</P>
<P>
"The cabinet is following up with concern the continuous
Israeli barbaric attacks against Lebanon and the random shelling
targeting civilian areas," said Al-Dakhil. (Kuwait-Lebanon-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said
Sunday that his country will strengthen ties with Belarus despite
a recent row over the detainment of Russian journalists there.
</P>
<P>
"We shall do everything to strengthen our ties with Belarus.
They are too precious, too important for us all," Chernomyrdin was
quoted by the Interfax news agency as saying while visiting the
Moscow International Air Show. (Russia-Belarus-Ties) 
</P>
