<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer Sets Another 800m World Record, Bailey Wins 100 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Wilson Kipketer of Denmark beat his
own world record in the men's 800 meters when he posted a time of
one minute, 41.11 seconds at the Cologne Grand Prix meet Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan-born Dane knocked out 0.13 seconds from the previous
record of 1:41.24 he set in Zurich, Switzerland, less than two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Paced by Kenyan David Kiptoo in the first lap, Kipketer burst
ahead and easily beat the mark that had stood for 16 years until
he first equaled it earlier this summer and then finally broke it
in Zurich, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Donovan Bailey of Canada, the Olympic champion, surged ahead
shortly after the start and powered past three American sprinters
to win the 100-meter dash.
</P>
<P>
Bailey, who was beaten by American Maurice Greene for the gold
medal at the World Championship earlier this month in Greece,
clocked a fast time of 9.99 seconds into a head wind on a warm and
muggy day.
</P>
<P>
Tim Montgomery, the bronze medalist in Athens, finished second
in 10.01, while Dennis Mitchell was third in 10.12. The third
American in the race, Vincent Henderson, was fourth in 10.24.
</P>
<P>
But there was an American win in the women's 200, when Marion
Jones eased to victory past two medalists from Athens.
</P>
<P>
Jones, the 100-meter world champion who became the third
fastest woman over the distance in Brussels two days ago with a
time of 10.76, clocked 21.93 over the 200m Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Merlene Ottey, the Jamaican veteran who was bronze medalist in
Athens, was second in 22.17, while Juliet Cuthbert, another
Jamaican, was third in 22.49.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400-meter hurdles, Athens bronze medalist Bryan
Bronson of the United States posted a time of 47.94 seconds to
beat Samuel Matete of Zambia and world champion Stephane Diagana
of France. Matete surged past Diagana in the finish to place
second in 47.99, while Diagana clocked 48.19.
</P>
<P>
The women's 400-meter hurdles also saw the defeat of the
reigning world champion, Nezha Bidouane of Morocco. Deon Hemmings
of Jamaica, the Olympic champion and silver medalist in Athens,
won the race in 53.54 seconds. Bidouane, trailing badly with two
hurdles left, abandoned the race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
