<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Training Guide on HIV/AIDS Launched in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua)-- The Ugandan ministry of
agriculture has launched a training guide on HIV and AIDS for
agricultural field extension agents, reported Radio Uganda today.
</P>
<P>
The guide is meant to provide basic information neccessary for
an infrastructure of rural development agents on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
During the launching ceremony here on Saturday, the permanent
secretary in the ministry, Opika Opoka said the training of the
extension agents will help them educate the rest of the field
extension staff and the farming community, the core of production
in Uganda threatened by AIDS through sickness and death to
protect themselves and reduce its spread.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony, Opoka presented certificates to
district extension workers who conducted a one-week training of
trainers' program sponsored by the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
460,785 of total 546,173 AIDS patients in Uganda have been
killed by AIDS since 1988. And Ugandans who live with HIV virus
now number 1,460,767, but a survey conducted in the country with
a population of about 20 million in 1988 showed the figure was
estimated at two million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
