<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Foreign Minister Ends Visit to Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Foreign Minister
Yukihito Ikeda left here for Paris today after concluding his
three-day official visit to Poland.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Poland, Ikeda held talks with his Polish
counterpart, Dariusz Rosati, on bilateral ties and international
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also signed a joint statement on cooperation
between the foreign ministries of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Ikeda on Friday and Saturday respectively, Polish
President Aleksander Kwasniewski and Deputy Prime Minister and
Concurrent Minister of Finance Grzegorz Kolodko called for more
Japanese investment in Poland.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan hoped that Poland could reduce the tariffs on
the import of Japan-made vehicles.
</P>
<P>
So far, Japan has invested 30 million U.S. dollars in Poland
and ranked 20th on the list of countries which have invested in
Poland. The trade volume between the two countries stood at 650
million dollars last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
