<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Reiterates Position on Deployment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will deploy the Russian
S-300 surface-to-air missiles as planned, as long as Turkey
continues to occupy part of the island and poses a threat to the
island's survival, Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides has
reiterated.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Greek Cypriot daily Agon (Struggle),
published here today, Kasoulides said "various western countries,
including the U.S., are disgruntled with the purchase of the
Russian missiles, but the S-300 system will be deployed unless the
reasons for which we were obliged to order them no longer exist."
</P>
<P>
These reasons, he explained, will cease to exist when people in
Cyprus feel their security is not endangered to a degree that the
missiles are needed.
</P>
<P>
The missiles, which the Cypriot government purchased from
Russia early this year to protect its military bases, are
expected to be deployed sometime in the summer of 1998. Turkey
has threatened it will launch preemptive strike against Cyprus
if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also disclosed that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has turned down a proposal from President Glafcos
Clerides, during the latest round of U.N.-sponsored talks earlier
this month, to discuss reduction of military forces and
equipment and the demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
On future effort toward an overall settlement on Cyprus issue,
Kasoulides said it's a process to be affected by many factors,
like the Turkey-European Union relations and Greece-Turkey
relations. But these factors are "all part and parcel of a wide
spectrum of moves due to take place" in the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey and Denktash have to choose between a return to the
negotiating table or implementation of their threats for partial
integration of northern Cyprus with Turkey," Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
They cannot have both, he underlined, noting that a move to
integrate the occupied part of Cyprus would result in Greece's
blocking of Turkey's proposed accession to the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Denktash threatened at the end of the talks with Clerides that
he would not return to the negotiating table until the EU either
postpones or reverts its decision to start accession talks with
Cyprus scheduled for early 1998.
</P>
<P>
Turkey on the other hand has also threatened to integrate the
northern part of Cyprus if Europe goes ahead with membership talks
with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
