<HEADLINE> At Least 20 Bangladeshis Injured in General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 20 persons were injured
here, two of them including a photo journalist critically, in
today's Dawn-to-Dusk general strike called by Bangladesh's
opposition parties in protest against the fuel price hike, said
informed sources.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said the major incidents took place in front of
the National Press Club this afternoon while police lobbed several
rounds of teargas shells to disperse the opposition activists.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) and
the Jamaat-e-Islami enforced the nationwide strike as the
government, which on August 18 raised the prices of all petroleum
products, rejected their call to rescind its decision on the price
hike.
</P>
<P>
The sudden price increase sparked off street protests by
opposition groups and transport unions. In today's strike hours,
at least eight BNP leaders and workers were arrested in Dhaka when
they were allegedly breaking vehicles and harassing passengers.
</P>
<P>
Pro-strike elements also halted trains by creating barricades
in different places including Joypurhat, Dinajpur, Kushtia,
chittagong and Comilla districts.
</P>
<P>
In most parts of Bangladesh, today's strike, however, was
peacefully only with disruption of normal life. Most of the shops,
business establishments and educational institutions remained
closed while government offices functioned with less attendance.
</P>
<P>
In the second-largest city of Chittagong, no untoward incident
was reported from any parts of the area, said Ashraful Huda, the
head of the local police department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
