<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Embarks on Ambitious Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has embarked on its long-awaited privatization program,
inviting independent power operators to pre-qualify for the
construction of a new power plant in Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
The Privatization Committee for the Water and Electricity
Sector (PCWES) of Abu Dhabi, a government body set up last year
to oversee privatization of public utilities, invited the bids
in today's newspaper and radio advertisements.
</P>
<P>
"The PCWES of the government of Abu Dhabi formally announced
the commencement of a competitive process to select an
experienced developer or consortium to develop, own and operate
the Taweelah A2 power and desalination plant," the advertisements
said.
</P>
<P>
The developer would own 40 percent of the company that would
be set up to develop, own and operate the project. The remaining
equity will be held by the Abu Dhabi government and local
investors.
</P>
<P>
The successful bidder would undertake to build a power
generation and desalination facility at the Taweelah site,
northeast of Abu Dhabi city.
</P>
<P>
The project will have a 480 to 580 megawatts of electricity
generating capacity and 50 million gallons of water production
capacity a day. The power station must be completed by the year
2001, the advertisements said.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi set up the PCWES last year to oversee the
privatization of its water and electricity services, one of the
heavily-subsidized sectors which have consumed a large portions of
the government's investments.
</P>
<P>
Like other Gulf Arab states, the UAE is trying to reduce
reliance on the dominant public sector and give private
investors a bigger role. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
