<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman's GDP to Remain Growth Despite Lower Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Oman's gross domestic product
(GDP) is set to grow 4 percent in 1997 despite an expected
decline in the oil sector because of lower crude prices, an
official report said today.
</P>
<P>
"The Omani economy is expected to record a real growth of at
least 4 percent (in GDP) this year compared with 6.5 percent in
1996. Inflation will remain below one percent," the report by the
Abu Dhabi-based Arab Monetary Fund (AMF) said.
</P>
<P>
The 4 percent growth this year was considered high because
of an expected decline in the oil sector in Oman and neighboring
Gulf states whose economies are seriously reliant on oil exports.
</P>
<P>
Oil analysts said the decline in the oil sector is due to a
forecast drop in crude prices, which will likely average 17 to 19
U.S. dollars a barrel this year compared with over 20 dollars a
barrel in 1996. They noted that oil production in Oman and other
Gulf states will remain unchanged this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the AMF report said that the predicted GDP growth this
year is to be achieved because the government has carried out
economic reforms to diversify its income resources in the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
The reforms include privatization, improvement of investment
and taxation laws, and fresh financial incentives for industrial
and other productive projects.
</P>
<P>
The report said the reforms have started to pay off, with the
non-oil sector surging by more than 5 percent annually over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
"The oil sector is giving ground to the non-oil sector as a
result of economic diversification plans and other reform
programs," the AMF report said.
</P>
<P>
"There will be a decline in the oil sector this year, but all
other sectors will grow. This will positively affect the overall
GDP," said the report.
</P>
<P>
According to figures of the AMF, an affiliate of the Arab
League, Oman achieved a surplus of some 60 million dollars in
the first quarter of this year, with revenues standing at 1.2
billion dollars and spending at around 1.14 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The surplus compares to a projected deficit of 683.3 million
dollars for the whole of 1997," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
