<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President: Colonial Structure Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe still has the daunting
task of transforming entrenched colonial structures 17 years
after independence from British rule, President Robert Mugabe
said today.
</P>
<P>
"We possess political power and do now fly a new national flag
and sing our own national anthem," said Mugabe during the burial
of national hero and veteran nationalist, George Marange at the
national shrine in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe who has been in power since independence in 1980,
observed that while a few blacks had made it in the business
world, the majority in this southern African nation of about 12.4
million people, remained poor.
</P>
<P>
The poor were subsisting on scanty agricultural incomes and
poor wages, he said.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that not much had been done to redress ownership
and distribution of national assets, he said, "even the current
national efforts at wealth creation continue to unfold in the
context of inherited colonial property relations largely woven
around race."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said recent nationwide demonstrations by ex-freedom
fighters who accused the government and ruling Zanu (PF)
leadership of neglecting, were manifestations of failure to
create "greater" wealth for the people.
</P>
<P>
"They want food, dress, homes, good health, good education,
skills and jobs and above all, economic empowerment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "this gift of precious peace and stability we
cannot afford to lose and accordingly, we should never deviate
from the charted path of unity on which it is founded." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
