<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-24 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Opposition Parties Insist on Boycotting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Some Jordanian opposition parties
still stick to their stance of boycotting the parliamentary
elections scheduled for November 4 this year, despite repeated
efforts by the government to persuade them to cancel their
planned boycott.
</P>
<P>
The third meeting for dialogue between the government and the
concerned opposition parties here today ended without reaching
any agreement, as the opposition parties still insisted on
their stance after talks with Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The representatives from the Jordanian Democratic Popular
Unity Party, the Communist Party, the Progressive Baath Party,
the Socialist Baath Party and the Arab Land Party, briefed
Majali on their parties` points of view and perspectives on the
upcoming elections, but did not submit any constructive
suggestion for a compromise.
</P>
<P>
They are demanding equal access to the media as pro-government
candidates during the election campaign. They also want the
government to cancel the peace treaty signed with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Altogether six opposition parties declared to boycott the
elections last month, citing the Press and Publication Law, the
one-person-one-vote election system, the normalization of ties
with Israel and the government`s measures to marginalize
political parties as the main reasons behind their boycott.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties now have 23 seats in the 80-member Lower
House of Parliament. The Islamic Action Front (IAF) has 16 seats,
making it the largest opposition group in the legislature. It did
not take part in today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Multi-party system was revived in the country in 1989 as part
of the political reforms launched after widespread riots set
off by economic hardships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
