<HEADLINE> Cyprus: Human Rights Are A Must to Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides today reiterated that human rights and
fundamental freedoms must be guaranteed in any proposed solution
to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a public rally in the eastern town of Paralimni,
Kasoulides said "we shall not bargain our human rights," Cypriot
TV stations reported.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has accused Turkey of violating human rights by invading
the northern part of the island in 1974 under the excuse of
protecting the Turkish Cypriots on the island in the wake of a
pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The island is now divided by a Green Line patrolled by
U.N. peace keepers.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Greek Cypriot refugees who fled Turkish invasion
from Famagusta, a town next to Paralimni, 23 years ago held a
rally just a few kilometers south of their hometown on the Greek
Cypriot side to demand an early home trip.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also warned against any attempted practice of double
standards in human rights in solving the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the international community for the "absence of
substantive and practical response" on the human rights issue,
which "has encouraged Turkish intransigence and provocative
behavior and impeded efforts for a speedy resolution" of the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides pointed out that displaying tolerance in cases of
human rights violations "supports injustice."
</P>
<P>
He said unless human rights and fundamental freedoms are
safeguarded in practice as part of a negotiated settlement, "any
solution will have a short expiry date."
</P>
<P>
"We are not interested in a short-term arrangement, we are
only interested in a lasting and functional settlement," the
minister stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
