<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Spacecraft Launch Delayed by Shrimp Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled launch of a
science spacecraft of the United States space agency NASA was
delayed today by two shrimp boats strayed into the launch danger
area offshore.
</P>
<P>
NASA has to reschedule to launch the Delta II rocket carrying
the spacecraft of the Advanced Composition Explorer (ACE) Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The delay will likely cost NASA hundreds of thousands of
dollars, according to NASA officials.
</P>
<P>
A helicopter from the U.S. Coast Guard was sent to tell the
boats out of the area east of Cape Canaveral, where the spacecraft
will be launched.
</P>
<P>
But the helicopter was unable to contact one of the boats
before the rocket's 25-minute launch window closed.
</P>
<P>
The spacecraft had been scheduled for blastoff from Cape
Canaveral Air Station atop a Boeing Delta II rocket at 10:41 a.m.
EDT today.
</P>
<P>
The spacecraft will be positioned 1.6 million km above the
Earth. It will provide a 30 to 60 minute warning before a
potentially dangerous solar storm strikes the Earth.
</P>
<P>
Eruptions on the surface of the sun can disrupt the Earth's
magnetic field, knocking out electrical power and endangering
spacewalking astronauts in orbit.
</P>
<P>
The ACE spacecraft's primary purpose is to sample the high
energy matter from the sun, the space between stars and from the
Milky Way that comes close to the Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
