<HEADLINE> Inflation in Western Germany to Top 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The inflation rate in the western
half of Germany is expected to jump to a 28-month high of 2
percent in August, up from 1.7 percent in July, the German federal
statistics office said today.
</P>
<P>
The Wiesbaden-based office, which based its projection on
preliminary data from four western German states, said rising fuel
prices due to the stronger U.S. dollar were to be blamed for the
latest increase in German inflation.
</P>
<P>
The larger-than-expected inflation rate is likely to reinforce
market speculations that the German central bank, the Bundesbank,
would be forced to raise interest rates which could curb price
hikes.
</P>
<P>
But many observers in the German financial capital of Frankfurt
did expect the Bundesbank to take such a move at its Tuesday
meeting when it is due to conduct its weekly review of a key
benchmark rate, the securities repurchase rate.
</P>
<P>
Given the recent weakness of the dollar, the central bankers
would take some time to examine the price-related factors exactly,
an economist with the German Commerzbank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
