<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan "Referendum" Attempt Refuted (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua News Agency today
released an article by Qin Hua, accusing some people in Taiwan of
attempting to separate the motherland under the guise of a
"referendum."
</P>
<P>
The article points out that the process of the political system
transformation recently launched in Taiwan was preceded by some
people in the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) attempting to
introduce "constitution amendments" and "change of territory" by
applying so-called "initiative and referendum."
</P>
<P>
They claimed that the introduction of a referendum into the
constitution is a very significant task in political reform in the
"face of the transfer of power in Hong Kong in 1997"; and is
closely "related to major policies of any state, as well as the
future of Taiwan." However, the article notes that people will
firmly oppose any move to accelerate the pace of separating the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The article points out that "pro-independence forces in Taiwan"
have for years attempted to change the island's status as part of
China and establish the "Republic of Taiwan" by means of
"referendum."
</P>
<P>
In October 1991, the DPP adopted party guidelines based on the
idea that "The people of Taiwan should decide by referendum
whether to establish a self-determined sovereign state, the
Republic of Taiwan, and formulate new constitution," it says.
</P>
<P>
In March 1994, the DPP tabled a "draft of the referendum law,"
which included "major policies of the state, the theme on changes
in major administrative demarcations, major political topics for
discussion, and constitutional amendments adopted at a national
development conference."
</P>
<P>
According to the article, the "introduction of a referendum
into constitution" proposed by the DPP in May is actually nothing
more than a continuation of the "Taiwan independence" theme in the
name of "referendum."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan "Referendum" Attempt Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article stresses that Taiwan has been part of China's
sacred territory since ancient times. All Chinese people,
including Taiwan compatriots, launched staunch struggles against
Dutch, Spanish and Japanese occupation during colonial history in
order to safeguard China's state sovereignty and territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan was restored to the jurisdiction of China according to
the Cairo Declaration and the Potsdam Proclamation following the
victory in World War II, said the article, adding that the fact
that Taiwan is an integral part of China is widely recognized by
the World community.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China (PRC) in
October 1949, according to the article, all countries establishing
diplomatic ties with the government of the PRC hold that there is
only one China, and that Taiwan is part of China, and that the PRC
is the sole legal government representing China.
</P>
<P>
Although the two sides of the Taiwan Straits have not been
reunited yet, the status of Taiwan as part of China has never
changed, the articles stresses.
</P>
<P>
It notes that the future of Taiwan is totally dependent on
reunification with the Chinese mainland and there are absolutely
no other alternative.
</P>
<P>
The article also reiterates the policy of realizing peaceful
reunification through cross-straits talks, and points out that any
move by splittist forces on the island to split the motherland or
to separate Taiwan from the Chinese territory by means of
"referendum" will be totally rejected by the Chinese people as a
whole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
