<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Universities Raise Tuition Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Most Canadian university students
face significant increases in tuition when they return to class
this fall, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
Fees for undergraduate arts students for the 1997/98 academic
year have increased in every province except Quebec, the federal
statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The sharpest tuition rise occurred in Newfoundland and Ontario,
where students will pay on average 18.0 and 10.1 percent more
respectively than the past academic year.
</P>
<P>
In other provinces, fee increases ranged between 1.7 percent in
British Columbia to 8.3 percent in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
On average, tuition fees rose almost 9 percent across the
country, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
At Quebec universities, fees for Quebec residents will remain
at 1,700 Canadian dollars (1,224 U.S. dollars) for the 1997/98
academic year. These fees are the lowest in Canada.
</P>
<P>
In the rest of the country, the fees paid by Canadian
university students enrolled in undergraduate arts programs in
1997/98 range from 2,400 dollars (1,728 U.S. dollars) in
Saskatchewan to a high of 3,700 dollars (2,664 U.S. dollars) in
Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
Most Canadian universities charge twice as much fees for
medicine, dentistry, engineering and architecture programs.
</P>
<P>
And foreign students pay much higher tuition fees than
Canadians at most institutions.
</P>
<P>
In 1997/98, the average tuition fee for foreign undergraduate
students enrolled in arts programs is 8,000 dollars (5,760
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
By contrast, Canadian students enrolled in the same programs
will pay on average 3,000 dollars (2,176 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, tuition fees have soared in every Canadian
province, far outpacing the inflation rate. Between 1985/86 and
1995/96, tuition fees in arts programs have more than doubled,
while the inflation rate rose by 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 15 years, tuition fees have become an
increasingly important part of university revenue.
</P>
<P>
In 1981/82, tuition fees accounted for only 8 percent of total
operating revenue of Canadian universities. Fifteen years later,
it had almost doubled to 14.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan "Referendum" Attempt Refuted (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Attempts by "Taiwan Independence" forces to change Taiwan's
status as a part of the Chinese territory through a so-called
"referendum" are ridiculous when judged from a legal perspective,
the article says.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, it adds, today's world features three kinds
of referenda concerning major political issues, including changing
a country's territory or the title of a state.
</P>
<P>
The first type of referendum applies to regions whose actual
sovereignty remains controversial. People living in related
regions vote to decide which country they wish to join.
</P>
<P>
The second form of referendum usually applies to regions which
were formerly a colony of another country; a territory practicing
self-government; or to a region which was historically an
independent ethnic country, and later became part of another
country, but still maintained distinct ethnic and cultural
differences from other parts of the latter.
</P>
<P>
A referendum provided people in such regions with an
opportunity to decide whether to abandon their suzerain and
declare independence.
</P>
<P>
The third type of referendum is based on the principle of
sovereignty belonging to the whole people. In this case, a
referendum can only result in a change in a country's title, but
not to the founding of a new country.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the article says, the only way to guarantee
the legitimacy of the form of referendum is to ensure to total
participation of all citizens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Referendum Attempts Refuted (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past several years, the Taiwan authorities have run
counter to the "one China" principle by vigorously publicizing
statements that "the two sides of the Taiwan Straits should be
split and ruled separately", and that "the Republic of China in
Taiwan is a country with independent sovereignty", the article
says, adding that this was particularly true during the "National
Conference on Development" held last December, The Kuomingtang and
the DPP reached an agreement on "the rights of people to exercise
initiative and referendum". The agreement, it says, provided a
breach for the DPP to include referendum in the Constitution, and
thereby created a true source for disaster. Taiwan authorities
must set the nation's interests above all else, return to "One
China" stand by taking real action instead of simply churning out
words, and must oppose and prohibit splittist activities under the
guise of referendum, the article stresses.
</P>
<P>
According to provisions the DPP drafted to include referendum
in the Constitution, the act is approved if votes in favor exceed
half the total ballots. In addition, the ballet to decide whether
Taiwan will be independent is valid if two-fifths of the total
voters on the island cast votes. What else will the act mean, if
it does not mean to seriously misguide and cheat the people on
Taiwan? the article asks. Obviously, it says, the goal of Taiwan
independence forces is to agitate, coerce and even force Taiwan
compatriots to follow a splittist road. There is no doubt that
Taiwan independence forces have created related acts to
deceitfully sway Taiwan public opinion, it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan "Referendum" Attempt Refuted (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The world as a whole recognizes that Taiwan is an integral part
of China and Taiwan compatriots are unalienable members of the
Chinese family, according to the article.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the three types of referendum mentioned above fail
to apply to Taiwan," it says.
</P>
<P>
The first type fails to apply because Taiwan is indisputably a
part of China and therefore is not a region with controversial
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the second type, Taiwan is neither a colony, nor a
self-governing territory. Historically speaking, Taiwan has never
been an independent ethnic country and thus has no right to talk
about independence.
</P>
<P>
The third type fails to apply because Taiwan is only one of
China's many provinces. Therefore, voting in one province can in
no way be regarded as a referendum, and Taiwan has never had the
power to decide a change of national title or territory.
</P>
<P>
"The sovereignty of China, including Taiwan and surrounding
areas, belongs to the entire Chinese people, including Taiwan
compatriots," according to the article.
</P>
<P>
It notes that splittist forces in Taiwan have no power to to
change Taiwan's status as a part of the Chinese territory by any
means, and that they will never succeed in their splittist
attempts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
