<HEADLINE> Ninth PACAP Finance Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Ninth PACAP Finance
Conference opened today in Shanghai, China's largest financial and
industrial center, will focus on reform and development of China's
financial and capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Some 600 experts from China and 13 foreign countries and
regions are attending the four-day conference, which is jointly
sponsored by the China Education Assoc. for International Exchange
and the PACAP Research Center from the University of Rhode Island
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Governor of the People's Bank of China Yin Jieyan and
Peter Sullivan?, executive vice-president of the Asian
development Bank (ADB), presented respective keynote speeches
related to China's financial reform and development and ADB's role
in capital market development in the Asia-Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Merton MIller, the 1990 Nobel Prize Laureate in Economics
from the University of Chicago, well-known Chinese economist
Huang Da, and Dr. Edward Kane from Boston College delivered
keynote speeches.
</P>
<P>
Conferees will discuss issues related to the development of
capital markets in China and the world, as well as the role of
Hong Kong in Asia-Pacific capital markets after 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the organizers, over 50 seminars and panel
discussions are scheduled for the conference.
</P>
<P>
Local economists note holding the meeting Shanghai indicates
the city's increasingly important financial role in China and the
Asia-Pacific Region. It also indicates that China is willing to
become further involved in the international financial arena.
</P>
<P>
The first conference was held in 1989.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
