<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Cracks Down on Counterfeit Trademarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Various district people's
courts in Shanghai today issued joint judgements against people
dealing in counterfeit trademarks.
</P>
<P>
Cao Yongjun, legal representative and manager of a local trade
company, sold illegal counterfeit trademarks for engine oil valued
at 120,000 yuan. Cao voluntarily surrendered to court and was
exempted from criminal sanctions, but received a fine of 30,000
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Mu Jicai, director of a local fan factory, was sentenced to one
year in prison, one year of probation and was fined 400,000 yuan,
for illegally earning more than 440,000 yuan from selling the
registered trademark for "Huasheng" fans.
</P>
<P>
Lin Shuitai, director of a local motorcycle plant, was
sentenced to one year in prison and fined 110,000 yuan for selling
registered trademark to produce and sell 80 motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Gu Renxiao, who sold registered trademark to produce and sell
candies, was sentenced to six years in prison, deprived of
political rights for two years and fined 200,000 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
