<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Folk Dance Graces Egyptian Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISMALIA, Egypt, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Beating waist drums and
chanting rustic tunes, Chinese young folk dancers in traditional
costumes swirled into the summer heat of the Suez Canal for a cool
night of art and cultural cocktail.
</P>
<P>
To the standing ovation of about 10,000 spectators, the
33-member Chinese Folk Dance Troupe performed the adapted versions
of "Huang Tu Huang" (The Yellow Loess) and "Dongbei Yangge"
(Traditional Dance in Northeast China) at a grand parade show that
heralded the 8th Ismalia International Folk Art Festival Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
The high-pitched sound of Chinese drums and cymbals contrasted
sharply with the rollicking lilt of Scotish pipes, while the
flowery poplin skirts of Estonian country girls flutter to
outshine the shagreened outfits of Syrian shepherds.
</P>
<P>
Each of the 33 countries taking part in the festival was given
a slot of no more than five minutes for a tip-of-the-iceberg show
of their music and dance traditions, before making their
full-fledged presentation at a floodlit open-air stage later that
night.
</P>
<P>
Dancing to the strong beat on the broad boulevard, the Chinese
dancers raised stormy applause and bravos from spectators.
</P>
<P>
The boys and girls, native to China's northern countryside, are
all top-notch students of Beijing Dance Academy, the cradle of
elite dancers in China.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are in their late teens, but their artistic
aptitude has raised them to the stages of the United States,
Canada, the Philippines and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
A glimpse of the program reveals an amazing variety of folk
dances of Chinese nationalities. The hectic "Shanbei Waist Drum"
from Han nationality, the breath-taking "Tibetan Reba Drum" and
the Mongolian blues "Long Song, Long Love", are among their best
fares.
</P>
<P>
"The dances are all originated in local countryside," said Xing
Zhiwen, head of the Chinese troupe. "Those from northern China are
full of pride, passion and enthusiasm, and that from the south are
dexterous, humorous and sensitive."
</P>
<P>
"Through them you can see Chinese people's outlook on love,
life and history, and their aesthetic perception," said Xing, a
senior member of the Chinese Dancers' Association.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese boys and girls also performed an "Egyptian Stick
Dance" to see the host pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
The week-long folk art extravaganza runs till the end of the
month, with performances simultaneously staged in Ismalia, Suez
and Port Sayed, the quiet cities under the shelter of olive and
palm dates trees in Suez Canal's cool breeze.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 folk artists from 40 famous musical and dance
ensembles of 33 countries are participating the festival, which is
classified among the world's largest.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Arab, European and North American countries appeared in
the festival for the first time. But organizers regretted that
there would have been more "authentic flavor" if they hadn't have
to turn down request from other 21 countries seeking to be
represented at the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Hassan, deputy president of the festival, told Xinhua
that the purpose of the event is to promote world peace and
friendship and to facilitate the communications and understanding
among the world youth through the channel of folk art.
</P>
<P>
This year's festival is the largest since Ismalia began to act
host to the annual event in 1990.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
