<HEADLINE> China, Singapore Sign MOU to Expand Air Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China and Singapore signed
here today a Memorandum Of Understanding (MOU) to expand air
services between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Premier Li Peng and Singapore Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong witnessed the signing ceremony and the signatories
for both countries were Mah Bow Tan, Singapore Minister for
Communications and Wang Li An, Vice Minister of the General
Administration of Civil Aviation of China.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore (CAAS) noted that the
MOU allows for a 43 percent increase in passenger service capacity
for the airlines of both sides by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the MOU, Mah Bow Tan said, "Today's signing of
the MOU is further testimony of the close and friendly ties
between the People's Republic of China and Singapore."
</P>
<P>
"The increase in capacity will be mutually beneficial. It will
pave the way for further growth of trade, tourism and investments
in both countries as Singapore and Chinese carriers will be able
to respond more readily to changes in market demand," he said.
</P>
<P>
Five Chinese carriers currently operate to Singapore. They are
Air China, China Eastern Airlines, China Southern Airlines, China
Yunnan Airlines, and China Southwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese carriers are operating a total of 23 weekly
passenger services from Beijing, Chengdu, Guangzhou, Kunming,
Qingdao, Shanghai, and Xiamen, while Singapore Airlines and
SilkAir operate 26 weekly passenger services to Beijing,
Guangzhou, Hangzhou, Kunming, Shanghai and Xiamen. The Singapore
Airlines also operate one freight service to Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
