<HEADLINE> Former East German Leader Convicted of Manslaughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Egon Krenz, the last leader of the
former East Germany, was sentenced today by a Berlin court to six
and a half years in prison in connection with killings along the
Berlin Wall during the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
Krenz, 60, was convicted of manslaughter related to the death
of people shot by East German border guards when trying to flee
East Germany through the former border areas along the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
He was placed under arrest and brought to the Moabit remand
prison in Berlin immediately after the trial.
</P>
<P>
But during the 20-month trial in Berlin, Krenz accused the
German judicial system of being biased against former East German
leaders, and said that he had never been given a fair hearing.
</P>
<P>
Krenz had made clear earlier that he would appeal to the
European human rights court in case of a conviction. "I'll not
submit," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court today also sentenced two other members of the
former East German Politburo, Guenter Schabowski, 68, and Guenther
Kleiber, 65, to three years in jail on similar charges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
