<HEADLINE> Jordan: US Peace Role Should Be More Committed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez
Tarawneh said today the United States should play up its role to
reactive the stalled Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian-Israeli peace process needs a third party to
help push forward negotiations, and the U.S. should play its part
in this respect," Tarawneh said in an interview with the
Cairo-based Voice of Arabs radio.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh said Egyptian and Jordanian leaders have been
coordinating in a drive to support the Palestinian people and
revive the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that the U.S. is in a more effective position
to stage major initiatives to solve the current peace impasse that
began in March with the construction of a new Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"As regards launching initiatives, the American side is the
most capable party in this respect," he said. He expressed the
hope that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will deliver
the visit to the region and that negotiations will be resumed
"without concentrating only on the security side."
</P>
<P>
Israeli, Palestinian and U.S. security officials have been
meeting under a framework set up earlier this month by U.S. Middle
East peace envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Israel demanded that Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat crack down on extremists before resuming talks and
lifting economic sanctions imposed after the July 30 bombing
attacks.
</P>
<P>
The suicide bombing attacks in Jewish west Jerusalem killed 16
people and wounded 170 others. Immediately after the attacks,
Israel imposed economic sanctions against the Palestinian
territory and canceled the planned resumption of peace talks
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian foreign minister attributed the present impasse
in the Palestinian-Israeli peace process to the lack of
confidence between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
He also rejected a Jerusalem newspaper report that Jordan backs
an Israeli plan to build a dam on the Syrian part of the Yarmouk
River that edges northwestern Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The proposed dam would be built on the Syrian land. Israel has
occupied a short stretch of the Yarmouk since its forces captured
the Golan Heights from Syria in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Israeli newspaper Haaretz reported that Israeli
National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon had decided to
build a Yarmouk River dam on the Syrian stretch rather than at a
non-controversial site chosen by the previous Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
But Jordan said Saturday it planned to build a dam on its own
in the village of Adassiyah, 150 kilometers northeast of Amman, to
divert its share of the Yarmouk river to another Jordanian
dam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
