<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO to Set Framework for World Tobacco Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization is
working on an international framework convention to promote
tobacco control among the member countries, said WHO
general-director Dr. Hiroshi Nakajima today.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that with the support of all the member countries, the
international convention can be put for ratification just after
the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the on-going 10th World Conference on Tobacco or
Health, Dr. Nakajima said that the framework convention is
intended to establish a world control on tobacco smuggling,
tobacco pricing and taxation, testing and reporting of toxic
constituents in tobacco and other tobacco-related affairs.
</P>
<P>
About six percent of the cigarettes, produced each year in the
world, are smuggled form one country to another, causing an annual
loss of 16 billion US dollars in taxation, he explained. So
international community should take common measures to control the
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
It will be easier to control the use of tobacco if all the
countries and regions set the similar high prices for tobacco
products, and the smugglers will find it impossible to profit.
</P>
<P>
In addition, improved and more effective international
standards for the testing and reporting of toxic constituents in
tobacco products and tobacco smoke would benefit the monitoring of
hazard degrees in tobacco products, he said.
</P>
<P>
The framework convention will also include regulations on
tobacco advertising, duty-free sales of tobacco, reporting of
production, sales, imports and exports of tobacco products and
sharing of policy and program information on tobacco control.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Nakajima said that about 35 million people in the world die
from smoking each year. The number of the deaths from tobacco may
rise to 100 million by the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
He called on all the countries in the world to join their
efforts to reduce the harm brought by the use of tobacco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
