<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smoking Causes Major Hazard to Women's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Smoking may cause serious harm
to the health of the 200 million women smokers in the world,
according to the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
WHO released a report at the ongoing 10th World Conference on
Tobacco or Health here today, saying that one-tenth of the women
in developed countries smoke while in developing countries, the
figure is seven percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of women smokers in developing countries is
increasing rapidly, and is estimated to account for 20 percent of
the female population by the year 2020, said Prof. Judith Mackay,
director of the Asian Consultancy on Tobacco Control and WHO
official.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of women in the world, who die
from tobacco each year, has already surpassed 500,000, or
one-sixth of the total deaths from smoking.
</P>
<P>
In developed countries, which have more women smokers, the
women's mortality of lung cancer had increased by three times in
1990s, compared with that in 1950s.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the women's mortality of smoking-related diseases is
rising almost in all the countries in the world, which may finally
resulted in a death number of one million among women smokers by
the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
Surveys show that smoking can not only cause the similar
hazard on women as on men, but also lead to other diseases,
including the premature menopause and impaired fertility, and a
higher risk of cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Mackay said that the maternal smoking is associated with
a higher risk of miscarriage, lower birth-weight of babies and
inhibited child development.
</P>
<P>
Parental smoking is also a factor in sudden infant death, she
added, and is related to the higher rates of respiratory
illnesses, including bronchitis, colds and pneumonia in children.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is that women should drop the habit
of smoking for their own health," she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco More Deadly Than Any Single Disease: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco has become a greater
cause of death and disability than any single disease, the World
Health Organization warned here today.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco use has reached the proportion of a global epidemic,"
since it causes three million deaths annually around the world,
WHO announced in a press conference of the ongoing 10th World
Conference on Tobacco or Health.
</P>
<P>
The mortality will rise to ten millions each year 20 years
later, including seven millions in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is known or probable cause of about 25 diseases, such
as lung cancer that is believed to mainly caused by smoking, and
cancers at other sites, heart disease, stroke, emphysema and other
chronic lung diseases, according to a WHO report.
</P>
<P>
"On average, lifetime smokers have a 50 percent chance of dying
from tobacco. And half of these will die in middle age, before age
seventy, losing 22 years of normal life expectancy," the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In 28 countries and regions of WHO's Western Pacific Region,
about as many people die each year from smoking as from alcohol,
murder, suicide, drug abuse, drowning, traffic accidents,
industrial accidents and AIDS combined, another report said.
</P>
<P>
China in this region, the biggest tobacco producer and consumer
in the world, has overtaken the United States as the country with
the largest number of deaths from smoking, it quoted Prof. Richard
Peto from WHO Collaborating Center for Chronic Disease Control
as saying.
</P>
<P>
China's Health Minister Chen Minzhang told today's press
conference that the country with 320 million smokers has reported
750,000 deaths from smoking each year. Such figure will be two
millions annually by the year 2025.
</P>
<P>
Dr Hiroshi Nakajima, WHO Director-General, termed the
growing tobacco epidemic "a fire in the global village", and
called upon "all neighbors" to combat this "avoidable public
health disaster".  
</P>
</TEXT>
