<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Global Economic Player: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong would continue to be
not only a Pacific powerhouse, but also a global economic player
after it became a Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China on
July 1 this year, a SAR high-ranking official told Australian
business community today during his trip to the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon in Sydney organized by the local chamber
of commerce, Donald Tsang, Financial Secretary of the HKSAR,
said: "I see Hong Kong continuing to develop its role as the
premier service center in the Asia-Pacific region. I am equally
certain that Hong Kong will remain one of the most open, free,
exciting and cosmopolitan cities on earth."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Government Information Service today released the
full text of Tsang's speech, entitled "Hong Kong: Looking Towards
the Future".
</P>
<P>
Tsang told Australian businessmen that under the unique concept
of "one country, two systems", business has been as usual in Hong
Kong after the handover.
</P>
<P>
"The Basic Law lays the foundations for the continued
prosperity and stability of Hong Kong. It is our road map for the
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Basic Law embodies all the four pillars of
Hong Kong's success -- free flow of information, a level playing
field, rule of law and prudent fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
The financial secretary listed a number of reasons that Hong
Kong was well placed to become a Pacific powerhouse -- its close
ties with the Chinese inland areas, its surging services
industries, its good financial shape and its 6.4 million people
who time and again demonstrated a "can-do" spirit and an
entrepreneurial flair.  
</P>
</TEXT>
