<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Deplores Failure of Talks on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The European Union Commissioner
responsible for relations with Cyprus and Turkey has deplored the
failure of the talks on the eventual reunification of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
In a press release today, Hans van den Broek said that he was
"deeply concerned about the disappointing outcome of the direct
talks between Cypriot President Glavkos Klerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash."
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-brokered talks, which took place last week in Glion,
Switzerland, ended in deadlock after the Turkish Cypriot leader
refused to drop objections to the possible entry of the
Mediterranean island into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Denktash insisted that the talks could not proceed while the
European Union remained committed to opening accession
negotiations with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner described the preconditions set by Denktash in
the talks as "unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
The commissioner urges both sides to reach an early agreement
on the continuation of the direct talks.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot controlled South
and a Turkish-occupied north since 1974 when Turkey occupied the
northern third of the island in the wake of an abortive coup by
supporters of union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
