<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No-Smoking Among Youth Vital to China's Smoking Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China's Health Minister Chen
Minzhang said reducing teenager smoking is vital to the control of
the growing tobacco epidemic in the country, home to 320 million
smokers and a giant tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
"In order to prevent young people from joining the army of
smokers, we have to take preventive measures more effectively to
control smoking among the youth," he told a press conference of
the on-going 10th World Conference on Tobacco or Health here today.
</P>
<P>
The average age when the Chinese puff the first cigarette is
20, three years earlier than 1984's figure, Chen quoted results of
a national survey of smoking behaviors as saying.
</P>
<P>
Smoking rate among the people aged 15-25 increased more quickly
than people of other age groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, China's health and educational departments have
asked schools to be smoking-free. Soong Ching Ling Foundation
launched a massive anti-smoking drive among Chinese children in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The foundation called upon the children not to smoke, buy or
sell cigarettes, and encouraged them to persuade their family
members to quit smoking and to stop people's puffing at places
with "No-Smoking" signs.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide drive not only got the backing from more than
one million children, but also directly affected the children's
parents and teachers who smoke, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The foundation was awarded the 1997 World Health Organization
"Tobacco or Health" medal at the opening ceremony of the
conference Sunday in Beijing, for its remarkable achievements in
this field.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, China still faces a very serious situation, Chen
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 300 million males now aged 0-29, about 200 million will
become smokers if current rates of new smokers persist," he warned.
</P>
<P>
"If they continue to smoke throughout their lives, 100 million
will eventually be killed by tobacco and half of these deaths will
occur before age 70," he said.
</P>
<P>
China reports 750,000 deaths from smoking each year now. Such
figure will be two millions annually by the year 2025.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
