<HEADLINE> South Korean Won Drops to Record Low Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korean currency dropped to a
record low of 904.6 won against the U.S. dollar on the Seoul
foreign exchange market Monday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar began to sell at 899.60 won and closed at 904.60
won, exceeding the 900-won level for the first time since the
introduction of the present foreign exchange system in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's base rate for Tuesday will be 903.40 won, 4.10 won
higher than Monday's.
</P>
<P>
A market analyst attributed the drop of won to the heavy demand
for dollars in trade settlements early in the week and the
wide-spread rumors that the government would tolerate the dollar's
rise until it reaches 905 won.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the central bank intervened in the morning
session, selling dollars in the forward market at 923 won for
six-month maturities and at 944 won for one-year maturities.
</P>
<P>
"However, the strength of the intervention was weaker than
expected," a dealer at a Seoul bank said, adding that the central
bank may allow the won to remain below 900 won against dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
