<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Substantial Progress in China's Enterprise Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China has recorded substantial
progress in the state-owned enterprise reform since the 14th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC) in 1992,
according to a commentary jointly issued by the Xinhua News Agency
and the People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
It was pointed out at the 14th CPC national congress that
transforming the operational mechanisms of state-owned
enterprises, while at the same time encouraging entry into the
marketplace and increasing vitality, represented the keys to
consolidating the socialist system and bringing the superiority of
socialism.
</P>
<P>
"Several years of arduous probing has enable the Party to reach
a consensus of the orientation, policies, objectives, correct path
and major issues concerning the reform of the state-owned
enterprises," according to the article.
</P>
<P>
It added that whether or not state enterprises can be
rejuvenated is no longer the focus of public discussion.
 "Over years of practice, we have come to realize that it is
unrealistics to revitalize all of the hundreds of thousands of
state enterprises," according to the commentary.
</P>
<P>
The nature of the shift in understanding lies in establishing
competitive enterprise operational mechanisms, allowing
enterprises unlikely to rebound to declare bankruptcy, and allow
profitable enterprises to take over loss-making enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The commentary pointed out that a total of 1,099 enterprises in
58 selected cities had completed bankruptcy procedures and an
additional 1,192 enterprises had been merged by the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
"This has not only improved the enterprise structure, but also
transformed the understanding of officials and employees
concerning enterprise mergers and bankruptcies," said the
commentary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
