<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Surges by 16.4: Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) --China's foreign trade had
increased at an annual average rate of 16.4 percent from 1992 to
1996, with the total volume climbing to 1,168.6 billion
U.S. dollars, according to the State Statistical Bureau.
</P>
<P>
This growth rate is higher than the annual average increase
rate of 12.1 percent for China's GDP (gross domestic product) and
the annual average growth rate of 8.8 percent for world trade
during the same period, a report of the bureau said, adding
foreign trade has grown into a leading force for a sustainable
development of China's national economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the ratio of China's foreign trade in
the total world trade volume had gone up to 2.7 percent in 1996
from 1.95 percent in 1991. China has maintained its position of
being the 11th player in the world trade for five consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, China's composition of commodities for
import and export has kept improving, which has adapted not only to
the development status and level of China's national economy, but
also suited the trade structure of major industrial countries and
regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of manufactured goods for export in China's total
export volume has gone up to 85.5 percent in 1996 from 77.5
percent in 1991, while the ratio of primary products for export
dropped from 22.5 percent in 1991 to 14.5 percent in 1996, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, China became the world's No.1 exporter
of garments and second largest exporter of textiles, and ranked
the 12th for the export of chemicals in 1995. (More )


nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
