<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Meets IMF Team for Resumption of Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi today held talks with a team from the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) at the State House in the port city of Mombasa,
the Kenya News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
President Moi said that he had useful discussions with the IMF
team and expressed the hope that following the talks a solution would
be found regarding the recent suspension of the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment facility to the country.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that another round of talks would be held
before the team departs the East African country.
</P>
<P>
Present at the talks were Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi, Central Bank Governor Micah Cheserem and other treasury
officials.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team was made up of its Deputy Director Goddal Gondwe
and Reimer Carstens, resident representative of the world body in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
This is the first meeting between Kenya and IMF after IMF
decided to suspend a three-year 215 million U.S. Dollars loans to
Kenya on July 31.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had cited high-level corruption in the government
departments of Kenya for halting the loan package agreed last
year between Kenya and IMF.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said in Washington last
Thursday that he was sending a team to Kenya for talks after a
personal request by President Moi.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that once negotiations started they
would end in agreement.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspension decision had driven the Kenyan currency of
Shilling down by about 20 percent against the U.S. Dollar at the
local foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Shilling strengthened against the U.S. Dollar to
about 65 last Friday when the IMF decided to send a team to Kenya
and the Shilling made further gains today, opening at 64.74
against the U.S. Dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
