<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Surges by 16.4: Report (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China has maintained a quick growth in the import of materials
badly needed by China's domestic economic development, resource
materials, high- and new-technology and complete plants over the
past five years, alleviating shortages of relevant materials at
domestic markets and advancing the development of industrial and
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The report also disclosed that overseas-funded enterprises are
playing an increasingly big role in China's national economy and
foreign trade. By 1996, about 47.3 percent of China's foreign
trade had been done by overseas-funded enterprises, but in 1991,
the proportion stood at only 21.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Up to the year of 1996, China had trade ties with 222 countries
and regions in the world, a rise of 23 countries and regions over
1991 level. Among them, the number of countries whose imports from
China each exceeds 100 million U.S. dollars has increased from 35
in 1991 to 60 in 1996, while the number of countries whose exports
to China each exceeds 100 million U.S. dollars has also increased
to 48 in 1996 from 40 in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Japan is China's biggest trade partner, but the Republic of
Korea, as well as Taiwan region have become two markets featuring
the fastest growth over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
From 1992 to 1996, China's favorable balance of trade has made
its foreign exchange reserves surge from 21.71 billion
U.S. dollars in 1991 to 105.03 billion U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, China had earned 343.07 billion
U.S. dollars from exports, greatly enhancing China's ability to
pay back foreign debts and improving the overall national strength
of China.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that over the past five years, overseas
investors have moved a great number of labor-intensive businesses
to coastal areas of China, making processing trade one of
China's most important trading ways with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
During the period of the past five years, China's import and
export volume by way of processing trade topped 535 billion
U.S. dollars, with the annual average growth standing at 20.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The development of China's export processing trade dominated by
labor-intensive enterprises has helped increase employment. Over
the past years, China's exports of manufactured industrial
commodities have offered about 40 million job opportunities, while
imported capital goods in 1996 provided jobs to more than 20
million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
