<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Sugar Industry Urged to Overturn Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Finance Minister
Sartaj Aziz today urged the sugar industry to improve its
performance and asked experts to investigate the gradual decline
in sugar production in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"There must be a progress in the sugar production by maximizing
the output and minimizing the cost," said Aziz while addressing an
annual convention of the Pakistan Society of Sugar Technologists
(PSST) held in Rawalpindi, a twin city of Pakistani capital
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that Pakistan's sugar production had decreased
gradually after fiscal year 1994-95 despite the increase in the
number of sugar mills from 66 in 1994-95 to 74 in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's sugar production declined from 2.98 million tons in
1994-95 to 2.38 million tons in 1996-97, according to PSST
President Muhammad Saeed, who also gave a speech at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, Aziz said, the sugar industry was facing
difficulties and this year the government had to spend 227 million
U.S. dollars on the import of sugar to meet the domestic demands.
</P>
<P>
"The sugar industry has a crushing capacity of 300,000 tons per
day, but during the last season only two-third of the capacity was
utilized", Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He agreed to a proposal about setting up an institution for
sugarcane and sugar research.
</P>
<P>
He also underlined the need of biological control of sugarcane
diseases as against the use of chemicals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
