<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late Birds May Not Benefit From New Calculation: EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Those countries that have to
wait until the second wave to join the economic and monetary union
(EMU) may not benefit from the new calculation scheme, the
European Union said today.
</P>
<P>
When asked if the new calculation scheme to be in force in
April 1999 will benefit the countries that cannot meet the
criteria now, a union spokesman said that no one will know whether
the new scheme is to work out figures upward or downward.
</P>
<P>
The new scheme will not have a clear-cut influence upon
calculation of gross domestic product (GDP), he added.
</P>
<P>
Countries aspiring to be in the first wave of joining EMU have
to meet the requirements of cutting their budget deficit to 3
percent or less of their GDP and their debt to 60 percent or less
of their GDP.
</P>
<P>
Now only Luxembourg has met both criteria. Ireland, Denmark and
the Netherlands are close to meeting the criteria.
</P>
<P>
The single currency, euro, will be launched in January 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
