<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Grant 100 Million Dollars in Aid to Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 25 (Xinhua) - A senior Jordanian official
affirmed here today that the U.S. government will give Jordan an
additional 100 million U.S. dollars in economic aid this year.
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan reported that Deputy Prime Minister for
Development Affairs and Minister of State for Prime Ministry
Affairs Jawad Anani said the sum will come from U.S. financial aid
to Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Anani said the additional aid came as a result of the efforts
made by King Hussein to push forward the peace process and his
continued contact with the U.S. administration.
</P>
<P>
Because it was not easy to increase the volume of its 1997
budget for foreign aid, Washington will cut 50 million dollars
from its aid to Egypt and Israel each and then grant it to Jordan,
Anani added.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Planning Rima Khalaf will sign here
Tuesday two agreements in this regard with U.S. Ambassador to
Jordan, Wesley W. Egan and Director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development in Jordan, Lewis Lucke.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be made available through the Peace and
Stability Fund, which U.S. President Bill Clinton unveiled in
June this year during Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan's visit to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The fund was established in appreciation of the constructive
role Jordan has been playing in building peace and stability in
the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan mediated the Hebron accord between Israel and the
Palestinians in January this year, under which Israel promised
to evacuate most areas of the city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In addition to economic aid, the Clinton Administration had
earlier decided to provide 300 million dollars in military aid to
Jordan in 1997. Part of that has been realized and both sides have
carried out two military exercises within this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
