<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf States to Invest More to Develop Oil, Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Arab states need to
spend nearly 100 billion U.S. dollars in the next few years to
develop their oil and gas industry to meet growing domestic and
foreign demand.
</P>
<P>
The United Arab Emirates' (UAE) Wam news agency reported today
that the fund is part of a total investment of between 200 billion
dollars and 250 billion dollars in energy and communications until
the year 2010 in the six-nation Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC).
</P>
<P>
It quoted a study by the Gulf Investment Corporation (GIC) as
saying "The oil and gas sector alone needs an investment of around
100 billion dollars while nearly 35 billion dollars are needed
for petrochemical projects."
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that most GCC countries have embarked
on projects to boost their oil production capacity and tap their
mammoth gas resources.
</P>
<P>
They said the six GCC members which include Saudi Arabia, the
UAE, Kuwait, Bahrain, Oman and Qatar have pumped more than 30
billion dollars since 1990 on maintenance and development of
their oilfields.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the world's dominant oil power with a current
crude output capacity of 9.5 million barrels per day (bpd). It
plans to expand the capacity later to more than 10 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has also embarked on projects to boost capacity to
3 million bpd in the year 2000 from current 2.3 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has already raised its production potential to nearly
2.5 million bpd from 2 million bpd. It plans to increase its
production capacity to 3 million bpd in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The three Gulf countries control more than 45 percent of the
world's total recoverable crude wealth and produce around 17
percent of the global oil supplies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
