<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Law Submitted to Legislative Examination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China has completed drafting the
first law on price and the draft was submitted to the country's
top legislature for deliberation here today.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the draft to the 27th meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress, minister in
charge of the State Planning Commission Chen Jinhua said China
needs a law on price to create a sound environment for the
formation of pricing system under a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
Such a law is indispensable for maintaining a good market order
and protecting the interests of both manufacturers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
He noted price reforms in recent decade have brought about
fundamental changes to China's price management system, with
prices for some 95 percent commodities and services now being
determined by market forces.
</P>
<P>
"Lifting price control does not mean not to regulate it
at all though the market economy requires government
administration through appropriate means," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
The draft law has seven chapters and 43 articles, covering such
aspects as pricing by traders, government-guided pricing, overall
price level regulating and price supervising and checking.
</P>
<P>
The draft law stipulates that government should take temporary
interfering measures or impose any emergency rules on prices in
case of drastic price swings or rises.
</P>
<P>
Chen stressed that the law is expected to improve government's
macro economic regulation which will in turn anchor the national
economy on a sustainable, steady and healthy development track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Teenagers on Mission to Spread AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Some AIDS-stricken
teenagers in South Africa are deliberately infecting others so as
not to have to suffer and die alone, local daily "The Citizen"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the results of a study conducted by the Biological and
Medical Anthropology at the University of Durban-Westville, the
report said some teenage males in Kwazulu/Natal Province are even
resorting to rape to spread the disease.
</P>
<P>
"You know you'll be rejected, you know you're going to die.
All you can do is go off and spread (AIDS). It's your only hope,
knowing you won't die alone," one youth told researchers.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu/Natal has more than two-thirds of the estimated 1.8
million HIV-AIDS cases in South Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The organizer of the study, lecturer Suzanne Leclerc-Madlala,
said her team of researchers had come across attitudes and
behaviors "quite opposite to what AIDS educators would hope for".
</P>
<P>
Many of those polled during the research said they were
convinced they were carrying HIV virus but did not want to go for
tests as it "didn't really matter".
</P>
<P>
According to the report, one doctor working in rural areas
told researchers she no longer told patients if they tested HIV
positive unless they specifically asked, which they never did.
</P>
<P>
"They just go out and spread it anyway," the doctor said,
adding "even if they say they're not, they're lying."
</P>
<P>
Women described to the researchers how they had been raped by
laughing teenagers who told them to relax and not to cry because
"everyone has AIDS now". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
