<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Sues for Millions of Dollars in Valve Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The family of a Sydney man who
died after his artificial heart valve fractured is suing a U.S.
multinational corporation for more than 10 million Australian
dollars (7.4 million U.S. dollars), in a world-first court
hearing, the Australian Associated Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address in the Federal Court today, Brian
Donovan, the family's barrister, said the valve, which was never
permitted to be marketed in the United States, was not adequately
designed, tested or manufactured.
</P>
<P>
He said in the months before the Sydney man received the value,
the "chief expert" on the device had strongly warned the U.S.
corporation not to use the valve any more because of a number of
fractures of the valves in his patients.
</P>
<P>
The three children and wife of the man, whose name is
suppressed, are suing the U.S. manufacturer Shiley Inc. and its
parent company Pfizer Inc., over the "70 degrees" Bjork-Shiley
convexco/concave valve.
</P>
<P>
The valve was implanted in the Sydney man, an accountant and
property owner, in July 1982 and he died at the age of 38, in
1990.
</P>
<P>
About 500 claims have been brought and settled in the United
States involving 60 degrees valves, but the Federal Court case was
the first involving a death after a fractured valve to go to
trial.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 valves had fractured with about 1,000 people dying
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The 70 degrees valves were recalled and withdrawn in 1983, AAP
said.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald, published last Saturday, quoted
statements by former employers of the U.S. manufacturer that none
of the workers in the company took their jobs seriously, with some
smoking dope or snorting cocaine on the job.
</P>
<P>
Many skilled staff had walked out during an industrial dispute,
some workers were replaced by illegal immigrants hired straight
off the streets, and many of them did not speak English, according
to Larry Hamilton, who was the company's quality control manager
in 1980-1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
