<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Bans Civil Servants From Accepting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Ruling Council of
Nigeria has endorsed an order that bans serving ministers and
other civil servants from accepting traditional titles in any
form.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian newspaper This Day reported today that the ban is
recommended by the special committee set up last May by the
Provisional Ruling Council, Nigeria's supreme legislative body.
</P>
<P>
Although the government gave no reason for the ban, the report
quoted sources as saying that it may arise from the "questionable
influence of such titles on both the person taking and those
giving them".
</P>
<P>
While implying that serious corruption exists in such cases,
the report also pointed out that "quite a large number of serving
ministers have amassed traditional titles irrespective of their
meanings for usefulness".
</P>
<P>
Instead of traditional titles, the committee recommended that
merit awards should be instituted for long-serving and
outstanding civil servants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
