<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Activities Close to Halt for Lack of Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The non-payment of contributions
by members of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) has almost halted the implementation of the body's
programs in the past year, said the ECOWAS Executive Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of ECOWAS Council of Ministers, Chief Ayo Ogunlade,
said last Saturday that member countries now owe the secretariat
more than 42 million U.S. Dollars as arrears.
</P>
<P>
The debt, including arrears of between three to 17 years as
well as contributions for 1997, has "virtually halted" the
execution of the community programs, said ECOWAS Executive
Secretary Edward Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
He described 1997 as a "particularly difficult year for the
community institutions and especially for the Executive
Secretariat" because of the non-payment.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin made the remarks in his message to the three-day
session of the ECOWAS Council of Ministers which began in the
Nigerian capital of Abuja last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The session is part of a series of meetings of ECOWAS
functionaries held to make preparations for the ECOWAS summit
coming on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It will be followed by a meeting of foreign ministers of the
member countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Benjamin, the impressive programs which the
16-member community adopted as a result of its interaction with
other regional groupings include the harmonization of national
macro-economic policies, establishment of a single monetary zone,
and trade liberalization scheme.
</P>
<P>
Other major programs cover the regional infrastructure
networks, regional gas line project, inter-connection of national
electric grids, regional environmental protection and regional
food security.
</P>
<P>
Ogunlade, who is also Nigeria's Minister of National Planning,
blamed the fund crisis of the secretariat for the failure to
implement a community levy.
</P>
<P>
The member countries agreed at last year's ECOWAS summit that
a 0.05 percent levy be imposed on all imports into the sub-region
from third countries.
</P>
<P>
However, a protocol on this adopted last year has not been
ratified by member states although it was expected to come into
effect on January 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister urged his colleagues to take bold steps
to make the scheme effective by coming up with concrete proposals
for the summit on how it could be operational from January 1 next
year.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the member countries to take immediate steps to
ratify all the protocols so far adopted to ensure the smooth
operation of the 22-year-old community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0138 </DOCNO>
