<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Offers Aid To Help PNG War-torn Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Australia had offered a 74
million U.S. dollar "peace dividend" out of its aid budget to try
and help resolve Bougainville's long-running secessionist crisis
in neighboring Papua New Guinea (PNG), Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer announced today.
</P>
<P>
Following talks with senior PNG ministers today, the foreign
minister announced that 14.8 million U.S. dollars a year over the
next five years would be dedicated to reconstruction and
rehabilitation projects on the war-torn island.
</P>
<P>
PNG gained independence from Australia in 1975 following its
69-year rule.
</P>
<P>
The funds are being allocated out of the 128 million U.S.
dollars in foreign aid Australia already provides to PNG annually,
and are not additional.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the dedication of the aid money to restore services
such as schools and hospitals on the island showed that there was
a dividend if Bougainvilleans chose the path of the peace.
</P>
<P>
"That is what this 100 million Australian dollars (74 million
U.S. dollars) is about," Downer was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Downer also offered cautious support for the Burnham
Declaration reached by the warring Bougainville parties at a
meeting in New Zealand last month, which has reinvigorated hopes
for an end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
PNG's newly-elected Prime Minister Bill Skate offered his
government's full support for the declaration at the weekend as he
announced two new rounds of peace talks set down for September and
October.
</P>
<P>
The declaration calls for a ceasefire, a lifting of the
military blockade, demilitarisation of the island and the
installation of a peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
Downer also committed Australia to transporting representatives
to the next round of talks in New Zealand and helping with the
repatriation of Bougainville refugees once the island returns to
normal.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said that Australia, PNG and New Zealand
had been talking for some time about a peacekeeping force on the
island, but added it was too early in negotiations to make any
decision.
</P>
<P>
PNG Foreign Minister Kilroy Genia said Australia had agreed to
provide rations, uniforms, boots and other necessities for the
cash-strapped Papua New Guinea Defense Force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
