<HEADLINE> Huge Input Needed in Nigeria's Minerals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The mining experts and bankers of
Nigeria have drawn out an investment plan for the government to
substantially increase the production of solid minerals in the
oil- and gas-rich country.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian today quoted the experts and bankers as saying
that about 97.2 billion Naira (nearly 1.2 billion U.S. Dollars)
will be needed for raising the share of solid minerals from the
current 0.3 percent of gross domestic product to four percent in
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been submitted to the Vision 2010 Committee, the
country's long-term planning body which is working on a blueprint
for socio-economic development toward the year 2010, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government, aware of the danger of the country's
oil-centered economy, has decided to boost the development of
minerals other than oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
It established the Ministry of Solid Minerals in 1995 for this
purpose. Import of some minerals which have rich reserves in the
country has been banned to encourage domestic production.
</P>
<P>
To date, 51 varieties of minerals have been identified in
Nigeria, with the reserves of 33 proven. 
</P>
</TEXT>
