<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illiteracy in China Down Four Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 24.4 million Chinese
between the ages of 15 and 47 have become literate in the past
five years, bringing the illiteracy rate down four percent since
1992 in this age group.
</P>
<P>
The State Education Commission (SEC) announced today that the
illiteracy rate of people in this age group is now 6.1 percent. It
is estimated that in the first half of this century, illiterate
people in China made up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
The SEC says that a six-year education program is now universal
among 92 percent of the Chinese population, and a nine-year
compulsory education program applies to 1,480 counties.
</P>
<P>
Ten province, municipalities and regions, as well as 2,000
counties and districts have basically wiped out illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The country's goal is to make nine-year compulsory education
universal and to eradicate illiteracy among people aged 15 to 47
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Some four million more Chinese learned to read and write last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Area More Involved in International Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- There are encouraging signs in
more developed coastal areas of east China becoming increasingly
involved in international economic relations, providing a strong
link to the world market.
</P>
<P>
The city of Shanghai, and Jiangsu, Shandong, Guangdong, Fujian,
and Zhejiang provinces account for about a quarter of the nation's
total area and population but export 76 percent of the goods and
their overseas investment make up more than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rapidly increasing exports last year amounted to nearly 115
billion US dollars, with Shanghai and Guangdong's exports
accounting for 36 percent and 80 percent of their GDP,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
As a pioneer of China's reform and opening-up drive, the area
has business contacts with nearly 200 countries and regions that
have put more than 100 billion US dollars into the area in
100,000-plus joint ventures. The area used 35.26 billion US
dollars in foreign investment in 1996, accounting for 82.7 of the
national total.
</P>
<P>
Multinationals like the US's Mobil Oil and General Motors,
Japan's Hitachi, Daewoo of the Republic of Korea, and Germany's
Mercedes Benz have businesses in the area.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector is another link to the world economy, with
156 overseas financial organizations having set up branches or
offices in more than 20 major Chinese cities, mainly in the
coastal area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
