<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Area More Involved in International Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone,
overseas-backed banking businesses have 5.3 billion US dollars
worth of capital assets and have made 15 billion US dollars worth
of loans. Last year, they held 2.45 billion US dollars in overseas
investment, half the city's total volume.
</P>
<P>
Some enterprises in China's coastal area have also tried their
luck abroad, opening more than 2,000 businesses in nearly 100
countries and regions. Jiangsu Province, for example, has spent
over 100 million US dollars in the non-trading sector, and Chinese
Panda Electronics Group has four companies in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Chinese-backed enterprises abroad are playing a double role in
bringing technology and market information back, in addition to
exporting goods.
</P>
<P>
This has improved the industrial structure and quality of
products. Of some 16,000 overseas ventures in Shanghai, more than
4,000 are in the industrial sector, with a third of the city's
industrial output and pre-tax profits, and 56 percent of
Shanghai's exports.
</P>
<P>
Even farmers in the area are eyeing the international market.
In Shandong and Jiangsu, several thousand export-oriented
businesses that link rural families with the outside world have
emerged. Shandong, now known as an "international shopping
basket", sells several hundred million US dollars worth of
agricultural products in overseas markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
