<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese JLG Vows to Accelerate Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Both sides of the Sino-Portuguese
Joint Liaison Group (JLG) have agreed to accelerate the handling
of the transitional issues in Macao in the remaining period before
the handover of power in 1999, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Han Zhaokang, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
JLG, told reporters after his first round of talks with his
Portuguese counterpart wrapped up today that the two sides reached
the consensus during their talks.
</P>
<P>
"We both agree that, as time left is limited, we should quicken
our working rhythm so that issues concerning Macao's transition
and the handover of power could be resolved on time and properly,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Having assumed office earlier this month, the new Chinese
ambassador also said that the two sides have agreed to work in an
"open, pragmatic and constructive spirit" in the coming two years
and four months.
</P>
<P>
Han and his Portuguese counterpart Antonio Santana Carlos
discussed almost every issue of concern and made a general review
of them during their first round of meetings.
</P>
<P>
Apart from legal issues, they talked about the localization of
civil service, the use of Chinese as an official language, the
nationality issue of some Macao citizens, the pension of retired
Macao civil servants, Macao's renewal of member status of some
international bodies, the establishment of a treasury reserve in
Macao, the transfer of archives, the transfer of government assets
and the establishment of a Portuguese-language school in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Carlos said that he hoped all these issues would be resolved
before the handover in 1999 in a constructive atmosphere of
"understanding and friendship."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the two sides agreed to hold a specialized meeting on
the transfer of archives Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the upcoming meeting is a major outcome of
the talks as the Chinese side has asked for the establishment of a
working panel on the transfer of archives for years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
