<HEADLINE> 72 Percent Nigerians Supports Abacha's Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Research by a group of Nigerian
scholars shows that 72 percent of Nigerians support General Sani
Abacha's running for a civilian president.
</P>
<P>
The Punch reported today that this is the result of the first
phase of a research sponsored by the National Mobilization and
Persuasion Committee for Abacha for president.
</P>
<P>
A total of 28 professors of different disciplines from the
University of Jos, the Federal University of Technology, Bayero
University and three other universities are involved in the
research, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Among those polled are people of different ages and
professions, including marketers and students, it said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the committee, Godwin Adzuanah said that the aim
of the research is to find out the popularity and acceptability
of Abacha's alleged bid to run for president next year.
</P>
<P>
He explained: "We are not asking for the prolongation of
military administration, but we are asking General Abacha to put
off his uniform and come out as a civilian to contest for the
presidency."
</P>
<P>
The aim of his committee, Adzuanah said, is to ensure
continuity and cohesion in government and the unity of the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the committee now has 29 chapters in 29
states of Nigeria. It also has offices in London, Switzerland,
Washington dc and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
Taking over the power in late 1993, General Abacha promised in
his transition to civil rule program that his military government
will handover power to an elected civilian government in October
1998.
</P>
<P>
On the controversial issue of whether or not he will run for
the next presidency, Abacha said earlier that it will be decided
by his constinuency. 
</P>
