<HEADLINE> Medical Blunders Prompt Hospital Review in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Hospital
Authority is to conduct an urgent review of the local medical
system in the wake of the public outcry at medical blunders that
have led to the death of patients and serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
Today's local newspapers said the Hospital Authority will study
procedures in all Hong Kong public hospitals in response to public
concern over practices and professional accountability.
</P>
<P>
The review follows Saturday's revelation that a girl had part
of her reproductive system cut out because a surgeon thought it
was her appendix. In a similar case at the same hospital, a woman
had a fallopian tube severed during another appendectomy by two
surgeons.
</P>
<P>
In another case, a 20-year-old man hurt in a car crash two
weeks ago died after being given incompatible blood, and in July
an old woman died after a hospital gave her an overdose of an
antibiotic.
</P>
<P>
In a forum discussing hospital standards Sunday, medical
professionals blamed inadequate supervision and a heavy workload
for the blunders.
</P>
<P>
A Hospital Authority spokeswoman said training, supervision and
reporting systems in public hospitals would be monitored, along
with staffing levels, drug procedures, blood transfusion
guidelines, safety, security, complaints and medical-legal
systems.  
</P>
