<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Campaign on Ethnic Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka today launched a
nation-wide campaign to help its people understand the island
country's ethnic problem and seek a peaceful settlement of the
country's long-standing ethnic conflict.
The campaign was inaugurated by President Chandrika Kumaratunga
at Anuradhapura, Sri Lanka's cultural capital in North Central
Province, this morning.
</P>
<P>
During the campaign, entitled "Ranga Thavalama" (Understanding
the Fight), a cultural troupe will travel through the island
presenting street dramas to create awareness among the people
about the country's ethnic problem, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was sponsored by the "Sudu Nelum" (White Lotus)
movement, which advocates peace and supports the government's
solution to the country's ethnic problem, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the "Sudu Nelum" movement said the campaign
will help the majority Sinhalese people be aware of the country's
ethnic conflict and support the government's peace effort.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, to last for more than three months, will tell
people about the beginning, the development and the present
situation of the country's ethnic war through a photo and book
exhibition, video programs and other activities, the spokesman
said.
A monument symbolizing national unity was also unveiled by the
president today to coincide with the launch of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has long been plagued by the problems between the
Sinhalese and the Tamil -- the two major ethnic groups accounting
for 74 percent and 18 percent of the country's population
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam has been fighting a war
for a separate Tamil state in the north and east of the island
country since 1983. More than 55,000 people have been killed in
the ethnic war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
