<HEADLINE> SADC Prepares Position on Lome Convention Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 25 (Xinhua) --The Southern African
Development Community (SADC) states will hold Further
consultations later this week to put together a common position
on the review of the Lome Convention before a SADC summit meeting
next month.
</P>
<P>
SADC spokesman Kgosinkwe Moesi made the announcement in
Gaborone, capital of Botswana at the weekend, local media
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said a meeting between businesses, governments and regional
stakeholders on Thursday will be followed by an SADC trade and
industry ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will have to agree on a final set of
recommendations to be tabled to the SADC summit in Blantyre,
Malawi early next month.
</P>
<P>
The Lome Convention, a trade and aid arrangement bringing
together the European Union (EU), 70 African Caribbean and
Pacific (ACP) countries, is due for renewal at the turn of the
century. Renewal talks are to start next year.
</P>
<P>
All SADC countries, except South Africa, belong to the
convention. Pretoria is poised to join the convention later this
year as a partial member.
</P>
<P>
If approved by the summit, the recommendations from the
ministers' meeting on Friday will become the SADC's contribution
to the African position, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This will then form part of the ACP negotiating directives
when the talks begin with the EU next year, he added.
</P>
<P>
No official position exists within the SADC yet, but calls
have been made for the Lome Convention's trade concessions to be
restored in a post-1999 agreement with the EU, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
The convention, which is now into its fourth term, grants
non-reciprocal tariff and quota preferences to the ACPs in EU
markets. The ACPs also benefit from a range of special commodity
protocols on products such as bananas.
</P>
<P>
The 12-member SADC was formed five years ago to coordinate
efforts for a common market. The regional group has a total
population of 150 million and a combined gross domestic product
of 170 billion U.S. Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
