<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxes Prompt British Pensioners to Drop Private Medical Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- As many as 100,000 British
pensioners are estimated to have given up private health insurance
since the British government scrapped tax relief on premiums for
people over the age of 60 two months ago, a newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Up to half a million are expected to join the mass exodus from
private medical care, the Daily Telegraph said.
</P>
<P>
The cuts in tax relief, imposed by the Labor government's first
budget plan, effectively caused insurance premiums to rise by a
third, which might affect 1.2 million people's decision whose
policies are due to be renewed later this year.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Conservative Party has warned that the drift
from private treatment would increase the burden on the National
Health Service (NHS), and wipe out the 140 million pounds (228.2
million U.S. dollars) savings the Treasury intended to secure by
removing the tax relief.
</P>
<P>
On average, the NHS spends 1,300 pounds (2,119 U.S. dollars) a
year on every patient aged 65 and above. An extra 100,000
pensioners in the public health care system would cost the NHS 130
million pounds (212 million dollars) a year, almost totally
offsetting the forecast savings, critics said.
</P>
<P>
But Western Provident Association, one of the leading health
insurers in Britain, estimated that the NHS will have to spend at
least an extra 300 million pounds (480 million dollars) to look
after patients who no longer have private coverage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
