<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Study Treatment of Snake Bites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Israeli scientists are
studying ways to develop a synthetic antidote to protect the lives
of cobra bite victims, said a latest report of Israel's Weizmann
Institute of Science.
</P>
<P>
The report said that poisonous snakes immobilize their prey
through hypnosis before killing them, and on the molecular level,
snake venom immobilizes a protein known as the acetylcholine
receptor which plays a crucial role in nerve-muscle communication.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in the Weizmann Institute have pinpointed the exact
spot at which cobra venom latches on to the acetylcholine
receptor.
</P>
<P>
A synthetic antidote could protect just that tiny spot,
preventing the venom from latching on to the receptor, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
It would be more effective and faster-acting than the current
method of treatment, which involves injecting the victim with
horse serum containing antibodies against the venom.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the synthetic molecule would eliminate the risk of
allergy associated with serum therapy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the study, Professor Sara Fuchs of the Immunology Department
and some other researchers zeroed in on a peptide (protein
fragment) that makes up a tiny fraction of the acetylcholine
receptor - a dozen amino acids out of some 2,000 - yet is crucial
for the binding between the receptor and a particular toxin in
the cobra venom.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this goal, the scientists searched through the
huge "library" of random peptides until they identified the one
peptide that had the strongest interaction with the toxin.
</P>
<P>
In a parallel study, Professor Jacob Anglister and Tali
Scherf of the Structural Biology Department used nuclear
magnetic resonance spectroscopy to describe the structural
aspects of binding between the protein fragment and the snake
toxin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
