<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Makers Step up 64-Megabyte DRAM Chip Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korean semiconductor makers,
including Samsung, LG and Hyundai, are ready and poised to expand
production of 64-megabyte DRAM chips in bid to meet the
generational shifting from 16-megabyte chips.
</P>
<P>
According to the industry sources, Samsung produced 1 million
64-M DRAMs a month in the first quarter this year, and monthly
production expanded to 2 million during the second
quarter. Samsung plans to boost monthly output to 3 million by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
LG plans to expand its monthly production capacity to 3 million
by the end of this year from the current 500,000-700,000. To
attain the goal, LG will convert the 16-M DRAM production line
into a 64-m DRAM line depending on production conditions.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai will maintain its domestic 64-M DRAM production at
300,000 a month while mass-producing 64-M DRAMs at its overseas
plant in Oregon, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The move indicates their strategy to prepare for a price
bit-cross between 64-M DRAM and 16-M DRAM which is expected to
take place from the fourth quarter of this year, Hyundai Research
Institute said.
</P>
<P>
Bit-cross, a semiconductor industry jargon meaning the price of
four 16-M DRAMs is almost equal to one 64-M DRAM, will lead to a
generational shift of chips because the adoption of 64-M DRAM is
technically advantageous to buying four 16-M DRAMs.
</P>
<P>
The price of bit-cross was pushed up as demand for big-capacity
PCs utilizing 64-M DRAM chips has been on sharp rise following
Intel's price cut of its Pentium II while Japan's NEC Corp. and
other leading makers have been cutting the price of 64-M DRAM
chips in a bid to gain a marketing edge, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
