<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smart Card for Intra-ASEAN Travel Proposed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 25 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Secretary-General
Ajit Singh today proposed that smart cards be used for travel
within the nine- member regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
Such facility would not only represent ASEAN's leap into the
future but also perform the same functions as the passport, he
said in his welcoming remarks at the opening of a two-day meeting
of ASEAN immigration director-generals here today.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the current meeting could endorse
the idea of a smart card and establish a sub-committee to work out
the details.
</P>
<P>
He said the use of smart cards when crossing borders has
already become an accepted practice in some of the growth
triangles in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
As such it should not be too difficult to extend it on an
ASEAN-wide basis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ajit Singh also said the meeting's most important agenda
concerned the abolition of visas for travel within ASEAN, hoping
it would help expedite the process even further so that visa-free
travel becomes a way of life in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from ASEAN members -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam --
presently enjoy visa-free entry for a month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysian Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali,
who opened the meeting, called for the creation of ASEAN lanes at
the airports of all ASEAN member countries to facilitate the
tourists from the regional grouping.  
</P>
</TEXT>
