<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The armies of India and Pakistan violently clashed last
weekend on the frontier of Cashimir. According to the Indian
Defense Ministry, the fighting last Saturday between Indian and
Pakistani soldiers resulted in the death of at least three Indian
military men and 20 Pakistani soldiers.
</P>
<P>
-- Bombarded over the past week by the Cambodian army loyal to
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, O'Smach, the last stronghold of the
royalist forces of Prince Norodom Ranariddh, was abandoned on
Sunday. The royalist forces, numbered at 1,000, and some 500-600
soldiers of the Khmer Rouge in the region of Anlong Veng dispersed
into the jungles after six hours of violent fighting with the
forces of Hun Sen around O'Smach, a frontier market town facing
Chong Chom in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- School children return to school today in several
departments in France, while about 1 million children will be on
their way back to school by September 4. The early beginning of
school is part of a vast program of readjustment of the rhythm of
schools in France, which is aimed at giving more space and hours
to sports and cultural activities by children.
</P>
<P>
-- Six days from the end of the term of Congolese President
Pascal Lissouba, the peace talks mediated by Gabonese President
Omar Bongo for the Congo Republic remains suspended. The
government radio has accused Bongo of "ceding to the pressure of
France exerted via the oil company Elf-Aquitaine." The fighting,
which so far is concentrated around Brazzaville and the northern
part of the country, can now spread to Porte-Noire, where the Elf
has a 3.45 billion franc (570 million U.S. dollars) income from
oil production each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
