<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished firmer and just off its highs despite a fractionally
weaker lead from Wall Street last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Brokers were at a loss to explain the renewed optimism in the
local bourse, which saw the September share price index contract
rise 24 points to 2627 on the Sydney Future Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 16.8 points higher at 2637.1,
just shy of its high for the day of 2638.1.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones' Philip Toop said the Australian
market had finished strongly after a tentative start.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not really sure why it's got such a positive tone to it,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 14.1 points, or 1.03 percent,
firmer at 1387.8, with resources giant BHP rising 12 cents to
17.20 Australian dollars, mining company WMC gaining 7 cents to
7.32 Australian dollars and Rio Tinto ending 12 cents better at
20.50 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Comalco, which is about 70 percent owned by Rio Tinto, was a
highlight of the local bourse, lifting 29 cents, or 4.37 percent,
to 6.93 Australian dollars after reporting a sharp rise in interim
net profit to 51.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 13.8 points higher at 1357.0, with gold
bullion in Sydney closing at 324.75 U.S. dollars an ounce from a
close of 323.65 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index ended 21.3 points up at 4240.1, with
News Corp. one cent firmer at 5.82 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, ANZ improved 15 cents to 10.07
Australian dollars, Westpac bank added 9.9 cents to 8.12
Australian dollars, CBA eased six to 15.33 Australian dollars and
NAB was 1.7 lower at 19.10 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 274.54 million shares valued at
572.63 Australian dollars (423.74 million U.S. dollars) with
rising issues beating falling ones by 511 to 503.  
</P>
</TEXT>
