<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's Welfare Party Strives for Survival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkish pro-Islamic Welfare
Party (RP) is working intensely to defend itself in a closure suit
against the party, the newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said RP leader Necmettin Erbakan was discussing a
defense statement with his senior advisors in Turkey's western
town of Altinoluk, where he was on summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
The party is facing trial before the Constitutional Court on
charges of having been encouraging Islamic fundamentalism.
Turkey's Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas filed a closure case against
the RP in May this year and has been calling on the supreme
judicial body to outlaw the party.
</P>
<P>
The RP will have to submit its defense statement, which is
expected to consist of six parts with a total of 100 pages, to the
Constitutional Court on September 5, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The RP leader and former Turkish prime minister Erbakan would
personally make a verbal defense before the Court, it added.
</P>
<P>
The RP has asked for an additional 60 days to prepare for its
defense thoroughly, but the Constitutional Court has not yet
permitted.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan had threatened that he would apply to the European
Court of Human Rights if RP is closed on anti-secularism charges.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan and his party have long been criticized for their
reluctance to curb the growing Islamic fundamentalism in the
secular country.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military, supported by other secularists, forced
the Erbakan government to resign on June 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
