<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Calls for Creating ASEAN Lanes at Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today called for
the creation of ASEAN lanes at the airports of all ASEAN member
countries to facilitate the tourists from the nine-member regional
grouping.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from ASEAN countries would feel privileged by being
members of the grouping as it facilitated their smooth movements,
Malaysian Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali told reporters
here after opening a two-day meeting of ASEAN immigration director
generals.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is expected to have the lanes once the new Kuala
Lumpur International Airport in Sepang starts operations,
scheduled for early next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Indonesia have already established the lanes in
their airports.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN tourists presently enjoy visa-free entry for a month
while tourists from Commonwealth member states have similar
privileges for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from ASEAN countries need not have to queue up by
having the special lanes, Tajol Rosli Ghazali said, adding, "The
privileges will be a boost to the ASEAN tourism industry."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
