<HEADLINE> S. African, Kuwaiti Officials Meet Over Arms Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise has held talks with Kuwaiti officials over
possible arms sale to the Gulf state, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The talks, held in Kuwait on Saturday, "almost certainly"
included discussions of South Africa's bid to sell Kuwait
artillery in competition with other countries although Kuwaiti
officials did not give details, diplomatic sources were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The local press also quoted the Kuwait News Agency as
saying that the talks covered "relations between the two
countries in several areas, including the military".
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Modise, who arrived in Kuwait Friday on a
two-day visit, held talks with Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber al-Ahmad
al-Sabah, the acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah al-Ahmad al-Sabah and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah
al-Salem al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
South Africa is reportedly competing for an artillery contract
against the British and the American counterparts. It is said the
deal could be worth up to 600 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, a large oil exporter, is buying 155mm self-propelled
howitzers, as part of a 12 billion U.S. Dollars rearmament drive
following the Gulf crisis which incurred the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
