<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 08:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Pleas for International Pressure to End Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has appealed to the United States and Europe to
intervene to end Israel's closure on the Palestinian self-rule
territories, particular Bethlehem, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
PNA chief negotiator Saeb Erekat made the appeal Sunday in a
letter to U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross, European Union
representative Miguel Moratinos and other leaders complaining
about Israel's punitive actions against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Erekat hoped that under the pressure from international
community Israel would end the closure of Bethlehem, stop
demolishing Palestinians' houses and cancel its plans to send hit
teams into Palestinian-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
"We urged them to interfere directly with the Israeli
government to put an end to such measures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said the closure of Bethlehem by Israel
following the Mahane Yehuda bombing last month in Jerusalem
which killed 16 people and wounded 170 others, was killing
tourism, the city's main lifeblood.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is destroyed completely," said acting Mayor Hanna
Nasser, adding that "The city is losing a quarter of a million
dollars daily."
</P>
<P>
The closure of Bethlehem was highlighted Sunday when Israeli
troops blocked a dozen tour buses carrying 600 Italian Christian
pilgrims from entering the town.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims then staged a prayer service at the road-block
until Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai granted the
group permission to enter the town via a different road.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, communications adviser to Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, contended that the closure of
Bethlehem is "not a sanction" and was based solely on the
recommendations of security officials.
</P>
<P>
He also termed Palestinian claims that Israel planned to send
troops into the autonomous areas as baseless "disinformation."
He said the claims are "obviously designed to divert attention
from the fact that the PNA has decided on a confrontation with
Israel, rather than a confrontation with the terrorist groups."
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan added that Israel "reserves the right to apprehend
terrorists in areas controlled by regimes which do not act
against terrorism." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
