<HEADLINE> Zambian Health Boards Asked to Account for Anti-Cholera Equipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- All Zambia's health boards have
been asked to account for the equipment the government has
provided for the control of cholera epidemics, local paper "Times
of Zambia" reported today.
</P>
<P>
At a one-day symposium held at the weekend in Ndola, northern
Zambia, on epidemic diarrhoea, cholera and dysentery, Zambian
Deputy Health Minister Nkandu Luo said that each year the
government buys new beds, gum boots, gloves, mouth covers and
dust coats without knowing where the items used during the
previous epidemic have been taken to.
</P>
<P>
The government will not buy any more equipment should there
be an outbreak of cholera this year, the minister warned.
</P>
<P>
She complained that once the epidemic is controlled, the
equipment disappears immediately. "Do these things have legs or
wings for them to go missing?" she asked.
</P>
<P>
"Should the disease break out this year, just know that the
materials that we have been purchasing in the last years would
have to be recovered and given to the workers by you so that they
can fight cholera," Luo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
