<HEADLINE> Israel's Jobless Rate Reaches Three-year High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Unemployment in Israel has
risen to a three-year high of 7.6 percent in the second quarter
this year, according to a report published today by the Central
Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The number of jobless has risen by 29,000 to 168,000 on a
weekly average, thus lifting by 1.2 percentage points the rate
of jobless from 6.4 percent of the workforce a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In all, the civilian workforce has totaled a weekly average of
2.197 million people, an increase of 2 percent over last year. Of
those, 61.1 percent are males aged 15 and older.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of Israel is expected to announce today
its decision concerning next month's short-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Governor Jocob Frenkel has recently said the unemployment
situation would play a role in the decision-making process.
Analysts expect the decision to be dominated by last two month's
relatively high inflation increases, 1.1 percent in June and 1
percent in July.
</P>
<P>
The bank's main concern is to stem the pace of price
acceleration, which currently stands at roughly 10.4 percent,
while the government's official annual target was set at 7 to 10
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
