<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Resume Air Show After Probe Into Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Belgium is to resume aerobatics
flights early next month after probes into a recent crash in an
air show in Ostend found that the responsibility rested with the
pilot.
</P>
<P>
An airshow will be held at Florenne on September 6 and 7, but
organizers have to hand in a full report about safety and security
of the show to the Belgian defense ministry beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Results of a preliminary investigation into the July 26 crash
at the northern seaside resort Ostend attributed the lethal
accident to errors committed by the Jordanian pilot, whose
maneuvers had violated safety requirements.
</P>
<P>
The German-made Falcon XT300 biplane of the Jordanian Royal
Falcon Squadron spun out of control while doing a dive and crashed
into a first-aid tent nearby, killing 10 people and injuring 55.
</P>
<P>
After analyzing video recordings of the flight, aviation
experts and designers and manufacturers of the acrobatics-oriented
plane concluded that the pilot, Captain Amr Hani Bilal, could not
pull up his plane under the great velocity after a series of loops
took him to only 10 to 15 meters above ground.
</P>
<P>
At one time during the show, the plane was flying overhead the
spectators, which was not allowed by air show regulations.
</P>
<P>
Belgian authorities had called off all air shows since the
accident, the first in Ostend where air shows had been popular and
attracted many tourists, saying they will not be resumed until
conclusive results of the investigation come out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
