<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Examines Border Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The State Council today
submitted a border security agreement signed by China and four of
the Commonwealth of Independent States to the Standing Committee
of the Eighth National People's Congress for approval.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on mutual reduction of military forces in border
areas between China, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, and
Tajikistan was signed by President Jiang Zemin and the heads of
state of the four countries during Jiang's visit to Moscow
four months ago.
</P>
<P>
A State Council motion signed by Premier Li Peng said the
accord is "fair, reasonable, and conforms to China's interests"
and that it "contributes to the maintenance of peace and stability
in border areas of China and the four CIS countries and further
promotes good-neighbor relations. It is also significant to the
maintenance of peace and security in the Asia-Pacific region and
the world as a whole."
</P>
<P>
The accord's aim is the reduction of military forces along the
Chinese border with the CIS to a defence level. In accordance with
the agreement, neither side will use force or use force as
threat or seek a unilateral military advantage.
</P>
<P>
The 16-article accord sets a limit on the maximum troop
strength in border areas and the amount of weapons, equipment, and
military technology. It also sets the time limit and methods for
force reductions and information exchanges on the military
deployment in border areas.
</P>
<P>
The accord will be effective until December 31, 2020, and can be
extended with mutual consent.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, the NPC Standing Committee will
examine an agreement on judicial assistance signed by China and
Tajikistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
