<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 07:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Visits Egypt Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat will arrive in Egypt today to hold
talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on the deadlocked
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cairo press quoted Arafat's advisor Nabil Abu Rodena as saying
that the two leaders' talks in Egypt's Mediterranean port city of
Alexandria will focus on the Israeli blockade imposed on
Palestinian lands and the efforts to salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat will convey to Mubarak appreciation and gratitude of the
Palestinian leadership and people for Egypt's supportive stances
to the Palestinians, Rodena added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak issued a decree last week to transfer 10 million
U.S. dollars in aid to the PNA to relieve the Palestinians'
sufferings inflicted by the month-long Israeli sanctions. The
Israeli punitive clampdown following the July 30 Jerusalem suicide
bombings has deprived tens of thousands of Palestinians of work or
salary.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador here Zohdi el-Qadra was quoted by Cairo
press as saying that Arafat's visit comes within the framework of
constant coordination and consultation between the two leaders
with the aim of pushing forward the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
They will discuss the "arbitrary Israeli policies" as the root
cause for the stagnation in the peace process and the risks this
now poses to the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Arafat reviewed the peace impasse and
Israeli sanctions with Egyptian Ambassador to the PNA, Mahmud
Karim.
</P>
<P>
Winding up his visit here Sunday, Chairman of the Palestinian
Liberation Organization Political Department Farouk Qaddomi said
he discussed with Mubarak's Political Advisor Osama el-Baz efforts
exerted for reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He also regretted the repeated postponement of U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright's visit to the region, saying that
this demonstrates the "failure of promoting the Mideast peace
process."
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Taibi, advisor to Arafat told local newspaper Al Ahram
over the telephone that Albright's Mideast tour is necessary at
the present stage, as stability in the region is not only in the
interest of the region but also of the U.S..
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. role in the peace process should be more
effective, influential and fair as regards implementing the
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Describing Egypt's political, and national role as "honorable"
and referring to the 10-million-dollar aid, he disclosed that some
Arab countries did not agree under the present circumstances on
offering the PNA either long term loans or aid to surmount the
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's security men have been meeting Israeli and
U.S. security officials under a framework set up earlier this
month by U.S. envoy Dennis Ross during his shuttle diplomacy here.
</P>
<P>
Albright has said her prospective trip to region depends on
progress on security. Her mission will be to salvage peace talks
battered by Israel's settlement expansion and last month's suicide
bombing attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
