<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks Benefit From China's Opening Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Statistics show that overseas
banks in China made 183 million US dollars in post-tax profits
last year, up 31 percent from 1995,
</P>
<P>
This indicates that overseas banks have benefited from China's
financial open policy.
</P>
<P>
Most overseas banks are showing a profit after two years of
operation. Overseas banks had opened 540 representatives and 162
agencies in China by the end of July, according to official
figures.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks in China had combined assets worth more than
32.9 billion US dollars at the end of July, up from 29.9 billion
US dollars at the end of last year. Their loans and deposits stand
at 23.08 billion US dollars and 3.99 billion US dollars,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks account for 3.1 percent of the total assets and
14.2 percent of the total foreign-exchange assets of all Chinese
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The top three banks in amount of loans are Japanese, Hong Kong
and French. The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, the Hong Kong and
Shanghai Banking Corp., and Sanwa Bank have the largest amount of
outstanding loans.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also show that overseas insurance companies in
China had more than 1.32 billion US dollars in total assets at the
end of 1996, with premiums of 575 million yuan (about 69 million
US dollars), or 0.74 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
China first allowed an overseas financial institution to set up
an operational agency in 1982. Today, 23 Chinese cities and the
island province of Hainan, which is also a special economic zone,
have permitted overseas financial institutions to set up
agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
