<HEADLINE> Britain to Tackle Abuse of Filipino Domestic Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
committed itself to improving the situation of Filipino domestic
helpers working in Britain, a press release by the British Embassy
in Manila said today.
</P>
<P>
The release quoted British Immigration Minister Mike O'Brien as
saying that there have been cases of abuse of domestic helpers,
many of whom are Filipino, in Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Many of them are content but some of them have been subjected
to ill treatment. The British government intends to act to tackle
this situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The issue is likely to be discussed when British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook comes to Manila Friday to hold talks with his
counterpart, Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The release added that the British government was considering a
number of solutions, including allowing foreign domestic workers
to change their employers and allowing them to have easy access to
an airline ticket home together with a sum of money provided by
the employers.
</P>
<P>
London is also examining ways of improving the conditions under
which the workers are employed, possibly by having a set of
minimum conditions, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Cook will be in Manila from Friday to Sunday. During his first
visit to the Philippines, he will hold talks with President Fidel
Ramos and Defense Secretary Renato de Villa in addition to Siazon.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
