<HEADLINE> Less Foreign Tourists Visit Israel in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Occupancy by foreign tourists
in Israeli hotels dropped by 10 percent in the first seven months
of 1997 compared with the same period of last year, the state-run
Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to figures published by Israeli Central Bureau of
Statistics (CBS), there had appeared a modest monthly upswing of
1.5 percent in hotel stays by foreign tourists, but this was
before the Jerusalem market bombing on July 30 in which 16 people
were killed and 170 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
Avi Rosental, director of the Hotel Association, said that he
hoped that the bombing and the recent hostilities near the
northern border would not cause incoming tourism to drop.
</P>
<P>
However, he was not optimistic, saying that "there are already
signs of a drop in tourism."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both the CBS and the Hotel Association noted that
as the number of foreign tourists staying in Israeli hotels has
gone down, the number of Israelis staying in local hostelries has
increased.
</P>
<P>
There were 10 percent more Israeli bed-nights during the first
seven months of 1997 than a year ago, bringing the total number of
bed-nights by locals and foreigners to 9.2 million.
</P>
<P>
Yet the number was still one percent lower than last year's
figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
