<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consortia Win Three Gorges Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Six other generators, worth 320 million U.S. dollars, will be
supplied by another consortium consisting of Voith Hydro GmbH, GE
Hydro and GE International Inc, and Siemens AG (VGS), according to
the company in charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The two were chosen out of six manufacturers from nine
countries competing in international bidding, handled by the China
Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
China's Harbin Electric Machine Co Ltd and Norway's Kvaerner
ASA will be major subcontractors for the eight generators awarded
to the Anglo-French consortium, while Dongfang Electric Machine Co
Ltd will be the major subcontractor for the six other units
awarded to VGS. The latter account for 31 percent of the total
contract volume.
</P>
<P>
The consortia have provided export credits and 15- to 20-year
commercial loans and will supply technology transfers. The 14
generators and turbines will have a capacity of 700 megawatts each.
</P>
<P>
The generators will go on line between 2003 to 2006, and the
project will need another 12 generators and turbines, which would
be built in China.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project -- the world's biggest of the kind --
is expected to cost about 30 billion U.S. dollars by its
completion in 2009.
</P>
<P>
It is intended to tame the Yangtze river, stopping seasonal
flooding by creating a huge reservoir in central Hubei province as
a catch basin. The 6,000-km (3,500-mile) river, China's longest,
and its tributaries have caused disastrous floods for centuries.
</P>
<P>
The project is forcing the relocation of an estimated 1.3
million people to make way for the reservoir and will submerge
22,000 hectares (54,000 acres) of farmland and 7,000 hectares
(17,000 acres) of forests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Collects More Funds For Developing Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China's largest trade and
financial city of Shanghai has made an effort to change its
fund-raising to fuel its economy and has opened more widely to
overseas and domestic investors.
</P>
<P>
This is why it has maintained rapid growth in recent years. The
city's total investment in infrastructure has increased annually
at 50 percent, to 150 billion yuan (about 18 billion US dollars)
over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qifan, a senior city official, says that ten big
financial companies have been set up to raise funds for
infrastructure projects and district- and county-level governments
have been encouraged to raise funds by themselves.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment in Shanghai hit 11 billion US dollars last
year and the city has approved about 50 overseas financial
institutions, with total assets of 15 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
There have been more loans from international banking
syndicates for construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The city has also encouraged the stock market, and investment
from other cities and provinces, and 15,000 domestic enterprises
have opened branches or set up plants in Shanghai in the 1990s,
involving 30 billion yuan in total investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
