<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Protects Offshore Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, a major port city in
north China, has maintained stable offshore environmental quality
despite steady economic and industrial growth.
</P>
<P>
Two billion tons of water emptied into the sea every year
creating a potential major source of pollution in offshore
areas. The development of offshore oil fields, transportation and
the livestock breeding industry also pose a threat to the city's
offshore environment.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has opened two wastewater treatment plants to process
over 700 million tons of sewage annually.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city's environmental monitoring network
generates over 3,500 pieces of data annually, and provide
policy-makers with a scientific basis for making decisions.
</P>
<P>
The city has adopted a number of local laws and regulations for
marine environmental protection, with the environmental department
and oceanography bureau conducting regular investigations of key
sources of pollution in order to improve the offshore
environment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
