<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Successful Housing Reform in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The collection of public funds
for home building, the selling of public housing and higher rents
in Beijing have fueled the reform of the local housing allocation
system, and together are expected to greatly ease the housing
shortage in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The city launched the reform five years ago and had raised more
than 2.3 billion yuan of public funds for housing construction by
June, 650 million yuan more than the sum gathered by the end of
last year.
</P>
<P>
All governmental departments and non-profit institutions in
local urban areas and the majority of those in the suburbs have
begun collecting funds from their employees to support local
housing construction.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 2.2 million workers in the city have made
contributions.
</P>
<P>
The municipal department which manages the funds has committed
3.7 billion yuan-worth of loans to 60 home-building projects.
</P>
<P>
The city has now sold 24 million sq m of public housing,
one-fifth of the local total up for sale.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the reform of the housing system, rent per sq m of
public housing has now climbed to 1.3 yuan from 0.11 yuan five
years ago, helping the city add nearly 450 million yuan in annual
rent payment.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the city has added an average of more than six
million sq m of new public housing annually and hit a record eight
million sq m in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city will place emphasis on the introduction of the public
funds collecting system in local overseas-funded businesses, some
big state enterprises, and businesses on the outskirts of the
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
