<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Contract System For Private Sector In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Guangzhou, August 25 (Xinhua) -- After the success of a labor
contract system in state and collectively-run enterprises and
joint ventures in Guangdong province, the system will be tried in
township businesses and in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The provincial labor department needs workers for township
enterprises, private firms, and household businesses, and is
getting them to sign contracts with their employers. The number of
contract workers in these businesses should be about 80 percent by
next June.
</P>
<P>
China's labor reforms are meant to end the guaranteed
employment system, but to protect the interest of both employers
and employees, it developed the labor contract system in the early
1990s. At present, 99 percent of workers in state and
collective-run enterprises and Sino-foreign ventures in Guangdong
work under a contract.
</P>
<P>
And the practice is spreading to township enterprises and the
private sector. By the end of June, 745,000 people working in
private firms, or 46 percent of the total, had contracts.
</P>
<P>
The figure is higher in the Pearl River Delta, where township
enterprises and private business dominate the local
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
