<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu-Israeli Water Conservation Projects Doing Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Gansu province, an extremely
arid area in northwest China, is expanding cooperation with Israel
to develop water-saving agriculture, including the ongoing
construction of a pilot irrigation project.
</P>
<P>
The project, which covers 100,000 mu (15 mu equals one
hectare), is located in the Hexi Corridor. The Yasheng Group
Co. from Gansu province and the Israel-based Netafim Co. each hold
a 50 percent share of the project which will be constructed at a
cost of 200 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
First phase construction, scheduled for completion within the
year, will introduce new irrigation methods, such as trickle and
spray irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli company will send agricultural experts to Gansu in
October this year to complete feasibility studies for a
manufacturing plant for advanced irrigation equipment. Plans call
for the plant to be constructed over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The project will also include the establishment of a training
center in Lanzhou, the provincial capital. Two Israeli experts
will work at the center for five to eight years to devise a
training program for Chinese agricultural experts and arrange
visits to farms in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli company will also recommend the introduction of
three to five crop varieties with potentially large export
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
