<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark-based Sabroe Plans to Help Indian Sick Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Denmark-based Sabroe
Refrigeration (Sabroe) has put in an investment proposal with
India's Foreign Investment Promotion Board (FIPB) to pick up 90
percent stake in Air Control Chemical Engineering LTD (ACCEL), a
sick company in the country, a government official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Sabroe will be picking up equity in ACCEL, through Best and
Crompton Engineering ltd., which holds 78.9 percent equity in
ACCEL. As a world leader in industrial refrigeration technology,
Sabroe plans to manufacture industrial refrigeration systems
including compressors in India.
</P>
<P>
Sabroe has offered to inject an equity of 115.2 million rupees
(3.25 million US dollars) of ACCEL, which has already accepted the
conditions stipulated by the Danish company in the existing
revival plan.
</P>
<P>
Sabroe will use ozone-friendly refrigerant R22 and ammonia. The
major advantage with ammonia is that it is produced in large
quantities and is available cheaply all over the world.
</P>
<P>
In India, the industrial refrigeration market still uses chloro
flouro carbon (CFC) and hydro chloro flouro carbon (HCFC)
extensively. Imports for these products are a drain on the foreign
exchequer.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the new non-CFC varieties of refrigerants are produced
under patent and prove to be expensive even in the United States
and Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Study Ganges Barrage Feasibility in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
will send a mission to Bangladesh soon to study the feasibility of
a barrage over the Ganges, a project crucial for about 40 million
people facing the hazards of desertification, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The ADB, one of the major donors to this undeveloped South
Asian country, is also expected to provide some 400 million U.S.
dollars in assistance to Bangladesh for its various development
projects during the current 197-98 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
During the official talks between the ADB and Dhaka, ADB
President Mitsuo Sato, who arrived here last Saturday, agreed to
send the expert team for the Ganges barrage study from the bank's
Manila headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"We had a very satisfactory discussion," Finance Minister Shah
AMS Kibria, who led the Bangladeshi government delegation, was
quoted by the local newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The minister said they had detailed discussions on poverty
alleviation, the government's commitment to education and
eradication of illiteracy, rural infrastructure development and
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kibria also said the ADB chief expressed his satisfaction over
the overall success of the Bangladesh economy, particularly the
economic stability, low level of inflation and economic growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka is planning to build a barrage over the river Ganges for
the maximum use of the water of the common river flowing through
India and Bangladesh, following last year's long-term
water-sharing treaty with India.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of water of Ganges at Farakka barrage in India's
side has adversely affected the 40 million people and the ecology
in the northern and southeastern parts of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
It was informed that the arsenic problem in the regions
appeared to be a result of massive lifting of ground water. It
could be minimized by using surface water for which the barrage is
needed.
</P>
<P>
The ADB chief has assured Dhaka that they were ready to send a
mission for the feasibility study of the project, which will take
three to four years, costing 16-20 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
