<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share-Holding System Enlivens Romanian Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 1,100 state-owned
enterprises in Romania adopted the share-holding system this year
in a bid to improve performance, said a Romanian news agency
report.
</P>
<P>
The listed enterprises, of which 85 percent are small ones and
the rest are of medium or large size, have generally improved
their economic performance, with profits going above the national
average level, the news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Romanian economists have viewed the share-holding system as an
important way for enterprises to get rid of their economic
difficulties. The government has also seen it as a key step in the
economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea announced in February that 3,600
state-run enterprises will adopt the share-holding system by the
end of this year, with small-sized firms being the focus of the
reform.
</P>
<P>
The general practice is that enterprises issue stocks in the
stock market or sell stocks directly to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government welcomes foreign investors' entry into
the stock market, encouraging them to buy more than 50 percent of
the shares of a company.
</P>
<P>
A newly enacted foreign investment law grants foreigners
investing in the stock market more preferential treatment than
direct foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The government has recently closed 16 large factories with poor
performance and serious losses, and decided to find new owners for
them by auction.
</P>
<P>
Romania started to initiate the new economic system in 1992.
The normal practice at that time was that companies distributed 30
percent of the capital to employees in the form of securities and
sold the remaining 70 percent in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian government plans to apply the new system to all
enterprises in the country by the year of 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar's Mining Industry Makes Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government has
invited foreign investments in recent years to develop the
nation's mining industry in a bid to fulfill local requirements
and increase exports.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in mineral resources, such as gold, copper and
precious stones.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar mining authorities sponsored two rounds of
competitive bidding in 1994 and 1996, inviting foreign
entrepreneurs to conduct prospecting, exploration and feasibility
study of metallic minerals, especially gold and copper.
</P>
<P>
On the two occasions, a total of 23 block areas, each having
1,400 square kilometers, were granted to 11 foreign firms for
operation.
</P>
<P>
Invitation for the third round of bidding was announced in July
with designation of 12 more new blocks for foreign entrepreneurs
to operate.
</P>
<P>
A dozen joint ventures between Myanmar state mining enterprises
and foreign firms have been set up so far to undertake exploration
and production of metals, pearl and finished gemstone in Shan and
Kachin states and Mandalay division.
</P>
<P>
These foreign companies mostly come from Australia, Canada,
Japan, Singapore, Thailand and the United States.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, foreign investment
in the mining sector amounted to 498 million U.S. dollars in 42
permitted projects at the end of July this year, standing fifth
sectorally after oil and gas, manufacturing, real estate and
hotels and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local private entrepreneurs were also encouraged to
engage in small-scale production, some also operating on a joint
venture basis with the state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 60 Work blocks were allotted with local individuals,
firms and cooperative societies, covering areas such as
Thabeikkyin, Kalaw, Kyaikto, Muse, Kutkai, Shwekyin and Kanbauk,
and those along the Ayeyawaddy, Malikha and Maykha rivers.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with gems and jade mining, local entrepreneurs are
allowed for operation, transport and sale of their finished
gemstone and manufactured jewelry at home or abroad, according to
the new Myanmar Gemstone Law promulgated in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also striving to increase its foreign exchange
earning by holding gems emporiums annually and a total of 250
million dollars have been realized through 34 emporiums and five
mid-year ones since 1964, drawing several hundred customers on
each occasion from over a dozen countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Mogok and Mogaung, three more new gems lands --
Namsa, Mongshu and Nawarat (Pyinlon) -- have also been discovered
in Myanmar since 1988.
</P>
<P>
According to the official statistics, Myanmar's gross domestic
product of mines increased 9.5 percent in the 1996-97 fiscal year
ending March over the previous year, and the export of minerals
and non-metallic products amounted to 195 million kyats (32.5
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The country's major export items consist of copper and tin
concentrates, and gems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Banks Predicted to See Growth Slide This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Thai commercial banks are likely
to record a negative growth of 15 to 20 percent this year as the
country's investment and consumption are tightening due to the
economic slowdown, a leading local research center said.
</P>
<P>
The 15 commercial banks in Thailand is likely to have a total
net profit between 1.11 and 1.48 billion baht based on the last
year's figure of 7.4 billion baht (246.7 million U.S. dollars)
provided by the Thai Farmers Research center.
</P>
<P>
The government's tight-belt policy enforced under its
commitment to the International Monetary Fund (IMF), and declining
levels of investment by the private sector due to the economic
slowdown, will put the banks under strong pressure in managing
their businesses.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans and the declining demand for bank services
are the two key factors that will negatively affect the banks'
performance this years, according to Pisarn Manoleehagul, head of
the research center.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers today said that due to capital outflow and the
baht fluctuation after the baht float, interest rates offered by
local commercial banks currently remains as high as 10 to 20
percent and their operating costs are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The increase of value-added tax also hurt purchasing power in
the country and consumption lending, such as credit cards and
housing loans which represented nearly 13 percent of the total
lending last year, will significantly drop, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
As the manufacturing sector will slow down new investment,
bank's lending growth in the industrial sector, which represented
25.8 percent of the total lending last year, will also fall.
</P>
<P>
Banks' lending in other sectors, like real estate,
construction, and services, will drop as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
