<HEADLINE> Floods Suspend Transport Links to Southern Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- All train and bus services to
destinations in southern Thailand's provinces beyond Chumphon
province were suspended Sunday as flash floods cut road and rail
links.
</P>
<P>
Both the State Railway of Thailand (SRT) and the transport
company offered refunds to passengers who could not make the
trips. They were instructed to check with the two agencies on a
daily basis to find out when services will resume.
</P>
<P>
SRT officials were quoted today by local press as saying that
ten train service routes to the south have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman at the transport company's southern region bus
division was quoted as saying that scores of travelers had phoned
to the office Sunday to ask if there were any bus services to the
southern routes. Many were disappointed to know that roads there
were impossible.
</P>
<P>
The flash floods reportedly resulted from a tropical storm
centered in Vietnam, which has brought heavy rains to southern and
northern regions of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The hardest-hit province was Chumphon, where over 5,000
families have been affected by floods.
</P>
<P>
According to the Meteorological Department, the tropical storm
in Vietnam has weakened and the depression is moving towards Laos,
with winds of 55 km at its center. The depression could still
bring heavy rain, resulting in flash floods and overflows on the
river banks in southern and northern provinces of Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
