<HEADLINE> Thailand to Close Less Active Overseas Trade Offices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Commerce Ministry is
planning to close down its less active trade offices overseas due
to its budget problem, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be implemented in early October after the
government releases its budget-cut policy.
</P>
<P>
Those offices targeted include commercial affairs offices and
Thai trade centers, and at least three offices in Africa -- Kenya,
Ivory Coast and Senegal -- are likely to face shutdown this year.
</P>
<P>
Thai Commerce Ministry officials said that the ministry has to
invest no less than 333,000 U.S. dollars in each office or center.
If the export value does not merit further operations, the offices
will be closed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry is also planning to open new offices in
those countries to which Thai exports sees sharp increases, such
as Peru, as part of its efforts to restructure the operations of
the country's overseas trade offices.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring will concentrate on regional trade rather
than individual countries, including combining commercial affairs
offices and Thai trade centers into those outstanding offices in
some countries to oversee regional trade affairs.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's commercial affairs offices are responsible for
support trade and the Thai trade centers mainly handle export
promotions. The two agencies usually operate separately with less
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Under the restructuring plan, the ministry considers Asia,
especially neighboring countries, as an important focus for trade
promotion, believing Thailand is a gateway for trade to the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
