<HEADLINE> Sampras, Seles Show Up First Day at U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- America's world number one
and defending champion Pete Sampras, and second-ranked Monica
Seles will play Monday's first-round action at the 10.12 million
dollars U.S. Open Tennis Championships in New York.
</P>
<P>
First prize for both the men's and women's champions is 650,000
U.S dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who triumphed in 1990, 1993, 1995 and 1996, has gained
the Australian Open and Wimbledon titles this year.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old American, 44-5 lifetime at Flushing Meadow,
will try to grab his third straight and fifth overall U.S. Open
crown.
</P>
<P>
Sampras will first meet Australian qualifier Todd Larkham,
while Seles will play Kristie Boogert of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Four other men's seeds will take their opening-round matches on
Monday, they are fourth seed Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, 12th
seed Felix Mantilla of Spain, 14th seed Mark Philippoussis of
Australia and 15th seed Petr Korda of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Monica Seles, a two-time champion, has posted two tournament
victories in the last month. She keeps a 31-4 lifetime record at
Flushing Meadow in 1991 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Eighth seed Anke Huber of Germany, 11th seed Irina Spirlea of
Romania, 14th seed Barbara Paulus of Austria and 15th seed
Ruxandra Dragomir of Romania will also compete in the women's
first round match.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Martina Hingis of Switzerland will face American Tami
Whitlinger-Jones on Tuesday. The 16-year-old Hingis, who took the
crowns at the Australian Open and Wimbledon this year, has won
nine tournaments while prevailing a 56-2 record in WTA Tour events
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Both men and women's evening matches will take place in the new
23,000-seat Arthur Ashe Stadium, which was named in honor of Ashe,
the former U.S. Open champion who died of AIDS in 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
