<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Reviews Impact of Philippines' Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- An International Monetary Fund
(IMF) mission started here today a one-week review on the
Philippines' economic and financial performance for the first
semester of the year and the impact of the peso's devaluation on
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources disclosed that the review would center on
changes in the country's monetary program to take into account the
liquidity tightening measures recently taken by the Philippine
Central Bank to prevent the peso from devaluating further.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Philippine monetary authorities would discuss
with the IMF team the proposed adjustments in base money limits as
a result of the changes in banks' reserve requirements announced
by the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
An indicator used by the IMF in determining whether the
prevailing liquidity in the financial system could lead to higher
prices of basic commodities, the base money limits comprise
currency issues, reserve balances of banks and reserve eligible
for government securities.
</P>
<P>
The IMF review assumes extra significance in the face of the
peso's devaluation, which would inevitably affect the performance
of the economy in the next five months as well as in the year to
come.
</P>
<P>
On the monetary sector, the government panel would also discuss
with the IMF team the changes in interest rates, reserve
requirements, open market operations, off-balance sheet activities
and banking sector development.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss the projections of the balance of
payments, specifically the impact of the peso devaluation on the
trade balance, transfers and on the debt structure and debt
service projections for 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The monetary and financial targets discussed by the government
and the IMF team are crucial for the Philippines' exit from
conditional financing programs of the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines and the IMF have agreed to postpone the
country's graduation until the end of the year due to the delay in
the passage of the comprehensive tax reform, the structural reform
considered a pre-requisite to exiting.
</P>
<P>
After the peso was drawn into the financial turmoil sweeping
the whole region, the IMF provided one billion U.S. dollars to
shore up the country's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
