<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Foreign Debts Soar in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of the Slovak
Republic said the nation's foreign debts increased to 7.8 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996, more than doubling that in 1993.
</P>
<P>
A bank spokesman said the debts are expected to reach 8.5
billion dollars this year and exceed 10 billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The average per capita foreign debt has grown from 690 dollars
in 1993 to 1,601 dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The remarkable increase is attributed mainly to the worsening
economic situation in the country. Its fiscal deficit this year
is expected to reach 36.9 billion korun (1.1 billion dollars) and
its foreign trade deficit 65 billion korun (2 billion dollars),
the spokesman said. 
</P>
