<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Chinese Director for Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Nuclear safety expert Pu Jilong
was appointed to a position as director of the Daya Bay Nuclear
Power Plant in south China's Guangdong Province on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Pu became the first Chinese operations director at the
jointly-funded nuclear power plant, replacing French station
manager Pierre Decaix who recently completed his three year
contract.
</P>
<P>
Liu Damin, another Chinese nuclear specialist, was appointed as
deputy director at the nuclear power plant. The assignments prove
that China has made progress in localizing the management of its
nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in 1985, the Guangdong Nuclear Power
Joint Operations Co. Ltd., which is responsible for operating Daya
Bay, has always attached great importance to training professional
nuclear power workers.
</P>
<P>
The number of qualified Chinese nuclear power workers has grown
rapidly, with highly talented people serving as key force in
operations at Daya Bay since the plant commenced commercial
operations in the early 1990s. The plant has reduced its foreign
work force from 60 to 14.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong Nuclear Power Joint Operations Co. Ltd. has
listed 1997 as a "year of training" and formed a group which has
drafted plans to implement on-the-job training for workers at the
nuclear power plant.
</P>
<P>
Despite reducing the number of foreign personnel working as
consultants, the plant will continue to maintain close contacts
with foreign nuclear power companies, and will continue to study
advanced management expertise and technology used by the
international nuclear power community.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
