<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shengli Oilfield Strives to Improve Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Shengli Oilfield in east
China's Shandong Province plans to increase investment in the
construction of more petrochemical and fine chemical projects in
order to improve the technological contents and lift the added
value of oil and gas commodities.
</P>
<P>
Shengli has grown into China's second largest oilfield since
producing its first barrel of oil in 1964. The field had produced
620 million tons of crude oil and 30 billion cu.m. of gas by the
end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
Wide application of advanced technology has enabled Shengli to
achieve a stable oil output for both onshore and offshore oil
wells over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
It has also fabricated China's most advanced movable offshore
oil-drilling platforms and has laid three undersea oil
pipelines. The oilfield has now constructed a group of seven
offshore well drilling platforms, 18 oil drilling platforms and
more than 30 ships and tankers. Shengli produced 1.5 million tons
of offshore oil and gas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition to establishing cooperative ties with dozens of
domestic oil fields, Shengli has prepared 16 tracts of land with
oil reserves for cooperation with oil companies from countries
including Canada, Peru and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, more than 1,000 petroleum experts have visited
the Yellow River Delta, the home of Shengli, in hopes of
attracting investment and cooperation opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Officials in charge of the oilfield expressed hope in gaining a
greater share on the international market by the turn of this
century, and increasing annual sales of oil products to between
3-5 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
