<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Inmates Doing Fine In Chinese Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A British man (the name is not
disclosed) in his forties who was sentenced to a term to serve in
Chinese prison for drug-related crimes has spent most of his time
making picture posters against drugs.
</P>
<P>
He was given a 15-year sentence in a prison in Qingpu county in
Shanghai, in August 1991, and is one of the twelve foreign
prisoners there.
</P>
<P>
His works were displayed at this year's International Drug
Abuse and Trafficking Day and this was reported by the British
media. He's now preparing for a second exhibition to be held next
year by the prison. He also likes to write for the prison's radio
station and newspaper, the Hope Guide, and prepares humorous stage
pieces to perform at parties with other inmates.
</P>
<P>
His day behind bars begins at six o'clock when he is woken up
by an electronic bell. Prisoners have thirty minutes to wash
themselves and make their beds. From 6:30 to 7:00, he usually does
some exercise with a set of dumbbells he made himself.
</P>
<P>
He is also in charge of checking up after the foreigners have
finished cleaning their living space, and records it every
day. They can watch English programs on TV during free time at
noon and in the evening, and the prison has two English-language
papers for them, China Daily and Shanghai Star. They can also
receive newspapers from their countries' consulates, if the papers
pass the prison security check. Lights-out is at nine o'clock
after roll call.
</P>
<P>
The foreign prisoners say they're satisfied with the food,
which is planned by a nutritionist. The amount of money spent on
foreign prisoners' food is 20 percent more than that for Chinese
prisoners. The prison prepares special food for vegetarians and
Moslems out of respect for their customs and religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
They are also given special food on traditional Chinese
festivals, like mooncakes for the Mid-autumn Festival, and on
Christmas and their birthdays they can have cakes.
</P>
<P>
Foreign prisoners have more time for themselves each week than
do Chinese inmates, except for two days of physical labor and
another day for studying the Criminal Law and Prison Law.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign prisoners are interested in learning Chinese, and
the prison authority provides them with tapes and books for
study. Writing brushes and inkstones can also be provided for
those who want to study calligraphy.
</P>
<P>
They can write two letters each month and can send as many
greeting cards to relatives and friends at Christmas as they like.
</P>
<P>
In his most recent letter to his son, the Enlishman says he
fully understands the harmfulness of drugs, and hopes his son
doesn't follow in his footsteps.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
