<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De Bruin Upset, Popov Completes Four Crowns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Alexander Popov of Russia
snatched his fourth gold while triple Olympic champion Ireland's
Michelle de Bruin was blocked from a feat of five titles at the
final day of European Swimming Championships in Seville, Spain on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Popov anchored Russia to win the men's 4x100-meters medley
relay, bringing his Seville tally to four gold medals including
50m and 100m freestyle and 4x100m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
His medley relays' title put his European championship titles
to 15 since his debut at the 1991 championships in Athens.
</P>
<P>
De Bruin, who collected three golds and a bronze at the Atlanta
Olympics under her maiden name of Michelle Smith, was blocked from
achieving her dream of five titles and had to settle with two
golds and two silvers in Seville.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Maria Pelaez stole the women's 200m butterfly crown
from Du Bruin as she colcked two minutes 10.25 seconds for a
margin of 0.53 seconds ahead of the Irish woman.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Italian Brembilla broke the 15-minute barrier
for the first time for his personal best with a championship
record of 14:58.65.
</P>
<P>
Marcel Wouda of the Netherland added a 200m individual medley
crown after he won the 400m on Wednesday with a time of 2:00.77,
edging Xavier Marchand of France to second in 2:01.08 and
defending champion Jani Sievinen of Finland the third in 2:02.12.
</P>
<P>
Natalia Meshcheryakova of Russia claimed the victory in the
women's 50 freestyle in 25.31, 0.12 seconds ahead of German
Olympic bronze medallist Sandra Voelker.
</P>
<P>
Cathleen Rund and Antje Buschschulte gave Germany a one-two
finish in the women's 200 backstroke in 2:11.46 and 2:12.05.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970825.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Debt Reaches 42.6 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' foreign debt
stood at 42.6 billion U.S. dollars at the end of March this year,
up 1.6 percent from the end-1996 level, the Manila Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
But financial analysts said the country's external debt
situation had been further aggravated by the Philippine currency
of peso whose value has plummeted by 14 percent since early July.
</P>
<P>
The debt was borrowed and must be paid in U.S. dollars which
were still strong against the local currency. The exchange rate
between the peso and the dollar once soared to a record high of
30.07 pesos to one dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a latest report released by the country's
Central Bank as saying that borrowings by private business
enterprises and financial institutions fueled the continued
expansion in the external debt.
</P>
<P>
The private sector now accounts for 39 percent of the country's
total foreign loans, while the external debt contracted by the
public sector and the Central Bank declined, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper added, the bulk of the foreign debt is long
and mid-term loans and need not to be paid in a short period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
